All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $275___.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
Tut was adopted from our Shelter over a year ago and the family was unable to keep him so he was returned. In that time he has put on a few extra pounds that the our volunteers are helping him work off with daily walks, which he loves! Tut is a very shy dog and loves to bark when he gets nervous but settles down pretty quickly once told to. He gets a little nervous around new people and other dogs (especially other alpha dogs) but does adjust quickly. Tut will need an owner that is willing to work with him on his socialization skills and behavior training moving forward, however he loves attention and positive reinforcement and will likely be stuck to his new owner like glue once he adjusts. 

If you are interested in meeting Tut or have any questions about him, please call the Shelter and arrange a time to meet him.

animal.description:
COVID-19 Protocol: Adoptions will be done by appointment only. If you see a pet you are interested in please call the Franklin Township Animal Shelter at: (732)-873-2500 ext. 6255 and leave a message with your name, phone number, and the name of the pet you are interested in.

You must leave a message so that we can return your call to schedule an appointment. Listings are updated on a weekly basis.

Adonis is 3 years of age and was surrendered to the Franklin Township Animal Shelter after his previous owner was unable to keep him. He is a sweet pup who absolutely loves attention (and elf costumes)! Adonis knows some basic commands, but he needs additional training on canine and leash manners. He is very smart and willing to please. Adonis has a lot of energy, is very strong, and pulls hard at the leash. Therefore, he can only go to a home with children aged 15+. Adonis cannot go to a home with cats. He may get along with other dogs, but he would have to meet them first.

Our adoption fee for dogs, cats, kittens, and rabbits is $60 per pet with a discount available for adopting two animals together. Cats, dogs, rabbits and kittens from the Franklin Township Animal Shelter are spayed/neutered. Cats, dogs, and kittens are microchipped, and up-to-date on all age-appropriate shots prior to adoption. Cats have also been tested for feline leukemia and FIV and dogs have been tested for heartworm.

animal.description:
Jace is a handsome 2-1/2 year old brindle colored mix of Dane and/or perhaps a Plott Hound and does well with older respectful children. He is sweet natured, easy-going, likes car rides, and surprisingly is a bit shy. He is easily spooked by new things, he's a big dog who thinks he's the size of a Chihuahua. He just needs time to get used to the way things work. Jace is not good with cats but is good barking at the fence, always a welcome talent if you like to know when people stop by to visit. He knows commands: sit, stay, lie & track, is house trained and walks nicely on a leash. Please call 928 537-8009 to arrange a meeting as Jace is living with one of our great Foster Families.

Still unknown how he is around cats. He's laid back but still playful. He does have some separation anxiety and will need a home with another dog.  Hawk requires at least a 4 foot fence.

Hawk is estimated to be 2-3 years old.  His current weight is 110 pounds.

The minimum donation for Hawk is $450.00. This includes all of his vetting. If you are interested in Hawk, please fill out an online application through our website.

We are currently only open by appointment only. Due to the recent pandemic, we are looking at the safety of our volunteers that are there to take care of the dogs. Only serious inquiries will be considered.

Then meet him at the shelter during adoption hours on Saturdays and Sundays 10 - 2pm. All members of the household need to meet the dog you are interested in. Vet records for any current or previous pets need to be provided. If all goes well, a home visit will be done prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Kringle is an affectionate, attentive 2-year-old boy who came into our Love-A-Bull rescue program earlier this month with a terrible wound on his face that could have quickly become infected and led to a less-than-jolly time! Luckily, he's healing nicely and is ready start his new life. 
Kringle loves people and is very cuddly. His favorite activity is sitting by the window, watching other dogs go by, and car rides! He also enjoys chew toys — even destroying the plush ones (whoops!). Kringle loves a good walk with his people and spending time in the backyard of his foster home. Above all, he just wants to be near the people who love him! He is also crate trained and potty trained!
Kringle may do well living in a home with another dog,  and probably a no-go on cats.

If you live near Austin, TX and want to meet Kringle, email adopt@love-a-bull.org or fill out our adoption application today: http://love-a-bull.org/adopt/adoption-application/

animal.description:
For my Petfinder.com friends, please contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information. My ID number is 334709

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Willa! What a total sweetness! Willa came to the Shelter after being found running the streets, all by herself! Poor girl...that's no way for a youngster to live! Willa is a very sweet girl, who is quite animated when people are visiting with her! She enjoys carrying her food bowl around after she's eaten it, possibly hinting for it to be refilled? :) Willa does well walking on a leash, but does become somewhat apprehensive when other dogs are reacting! This beautiful girl deserves to be in a safe and secure environment, where she will be tended to, loved and adored for her lifetime! 

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 334973 (female), and 334954 (male). Did very well with both. When she hears another dog behaving and vocalizing aggressively, she becomes reactive. Recommend slow introductions with other dogs 10/26/2020

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.

**Age is estimated** Primary Color: Tan Secondary Color: White Weight: 42lbs Age: 3yrs 3mths 1wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
Things you should know about foster Agnes (10 years of age):

1. She came to PugHearts with a dental infection, but she eats regular food with a little bit of water in it. (Dental scheduled 12/16)

2. She came to with a bladder infection, but her infection is now gone and she proves that she is potty trained every day, even in the rain.

3. She came to with an ear infection, but her infection is now gone and she responds to us calling her and barks if she is alerted.

4. She came to with a bad back, but she does not let that slow her down. Playtime is serious business to Agnes and she wants to play with you at least once a day. She has learned to play fetch and gets excited when she looks at anything sparkly-- especially Christmas ornaments!

5. She came to PugHearts with an enlarged heart and she uses that to love people more and more every day.

She is the best buddy and loves to follow her person around. She is also good at being part of a grumble and will love on any brothers and sisters she might get.

animal.description:
Hi there! I'm Libby. I am a funny young Lab mix; approximately 1-2 years old and I weigh 56 lbs. Some nice people found me roaming around by their home one morning; they took me in, fed me and kept me warm. They wanted to keep me but I didn't get along with their dog, so they called ARFhouse! 

I am the NICEST girl in the world! I'm not too keen on other dogs, but I love humans! I can't get enough attention; I love belly rubs, chasing toys and getting all the pets! I am a fun young girl and I will need some obedience training, but nothing too crazy and I will learn quickly because I'm sharp as a tack! Because I don't seem to like other dogs, I need to be in a home where I am the only pet. I wouldn't be suited for an apartment; I need a large, fenced yard where I can run and play! 

The fee to adopt Libby is $200.00; this includes spay/neuter, deworming, vaccinations and a microchip. If you are interested in adopting Libby, please visit our website. www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. 

**Please Note: Libby is currently located at our facility in Sherman, Texas. Adoptions are by-appointment only; if you would like to meet Libby, please fill out an application on our website. Once we have your application, our Adoption Coordinator will follow up with you ASAP with any questions she may have, or to set up a meet-and-greet.

animal.description:
Cocoa came in as a stray to a rural shelter. She was very timid when we first got her but is coming out of her shell. She is sweet to everyone she meets. 

Cocoa is 2-3 years old. She does like people and would be OK with older kids. She loves to go for walks and also likes to play with other dogs. She lives in the home with two senior beagles and is also really good and calm with them. She really should have another dog in the home.

Cocoa has quickly warmed up to people since we have had her. She loves to follow you around and will approach both men and women with a wagging tail. There are times if you move quickly she will duck down but she doesn’t run away from you.

Cocoa does not really like being alone although she will go in a crate. She will bark for a few minutes if you leave the house so an apartment is not good for her. She does stop barking once you are gone for a few minutes. She loves her people so much she would prefer someone was home a lot.

She is up to date on vaccinations, micro-chipped, HW negative and spayed.

If interested in meeting Cocoa our application can be found at www.homesfurhounds.com. She is located in Williamsburg.

animal.description: Blitz is a beautiful, brindle girl who lived in a home before coming to PACC. She's sure hoping to get into another home in time for the holidays, and we're doing our best to make her holiday wish come true. In her former home, Blitz lived with kids ages 2 through 8 and reportedly did well. Her former owners tell us she's housetrained and loved to sleep in her dog bed. Blitz is a super playful girl, but she can get overly excited, so we recommend no dog parks and that she meet any resident dogs before going home to live with them. We also recommend Blitz leave with a dog savvy owner who is willing to work with her on her stimulus control. Blitz is a very sweet girl and we know the perfect home is out there for her. If you think you can make her holiday wish come true, make an appointment to meet her today. Ask Blitz' volunteer advocate, Gail, about her: foster070204@gmail.com BLITZ IS ENROLLED IN THE GOOD DOG PROJECT AT PACC - Read a message from her case manager here: tinyurl.com/gdpmessage - Ask her case manager about him: rachel.jones@pima.gov

animal.description: Elvis is a 9 year old Chihuahua. He was living his life as a puppy mill dog until coming to TNT. He will need a quieter home, and a patient one. Older children would be just fine, but younger may scare him.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Pucho! I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a very sweet little man who would be an excellent family dog who would be great with younger children. I like to play with other dogs but I can be selective with who I choose to play with sometimes. animal.description:
He is so energetic. I mean my boy is always on GO mode! He absolutely LOVES TENNIS BALLS! I would even say that he’s INFATUATED with them. They are his favorite thing in the whole world. When playing with toys, Salem knows the commands “Drop it” , “Leave it”, and “Wait”.  He also knows “Sit” and “Stay”. Salem is good with other dogs. So good, in fact, that we ask him to help us when assessing new dogs! He has shown to be patient and well mannered with children. Salem pulls on a leash but that’s nothing a little leash training can’t fix! He does inhale toys when left unattended, so when playing with toys, he’ll need some supervision. Because Salem is super active it may be best that he finds a family that goes on walks, morning runs, or even just throwing a ball back and forth a few times!  When he sees a smiling face walking towards him, his little tail goes a mile a minute and he’s the happiest pup ever. The more time I spend with him. The more I love him. He’s just a sweet happy go lucky little boy who loves tennis balls and wants a home of his own.is at our West Bank location while he awaits his forever home. Salem is an affectionate dog who's favorite thing is tennis balls and a field to run in. He knows sit/stay/down/leave it and he's become a staff favorite. 
For more info about Salem, email our adoption coordinator, Tiffanie at Tstinson@jeffparish.net

Prairie Pooches Rescue has sweet Harlem in our care and in search of his forever home.  Harlem came into our care from Ontario due to the provincial breed ban.  He came from a neglected home that failed to teach him how to be a dog and didn't get him any vet care.  His ears and skin were in horrible shape and he hadn't seen much of the outside world.  Thankfully he had a very loving foster home in Ontario who showed him how some love and routine can make life much more joyful.  He learnt how to play fetch, run around, snuggle on the couch and really just come out of his shell.  

Harlem has come a long ways since being in our care.  He has settled to be a much more secure boy.  He is content now to chill and chew on a bone or happy to come along for a nice walk with his humans.  He has been good with the dogs his size and would do best with another playful female his size.  He walks really well with his head halti.  He's a smart eager boy and will do pretty much anything for treats.  He knows to sit and wait to have his leash put on, waits nicely for his food, and takes treats gentle too.  He adores children but does need a home with only older or no kids and he will zoom down small kids.  He deserves to find his forever home so that there can be room for more doggies to be saved.  Please consider adopting Harlem. 

Prairie Pooches Rescue is a volunteer and foster based rescue. All our dogs are in foster homes and approved adopters are required to meet the dogs at the foster homes.

Adoption fee is $250. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinations UTD, dewormed and microchipped. Adoption applications and home visits are done for all adoptions. Please fill out an application if interested on our website www.prairiepoochesrescue.com

****Due to an overwhelming amount of emails and phone calls we receive we will only respond to ones that have an application attached. Thank you****

animal.description:
This little one is Ginger, an 8-year old, 12 lb. Chihuahua, looking for a forever home. Ginger is a special needs girl. She is blind.  Her foster mom says: “She amazes me every day. She may be blind, but that doesn’t stop her from exploring and enjoying her life.”

Ginger is a very sweet, tiny dog. She loves treats and her doggie bed with a soft blanket to burrow under.  Ginger gets along well with cats and small dogs.  She hasn’t been tested around large dogs.  Once she knows where you want her to go and gets comfortable with the lay of your home, Ginger does well with potty training.  She does like to eat alone because she can’t see who might be coming for her food.

Ginger has been spayed, is current on vaccinations, has tested negative for heartworm, and has been microchipped.

We are committed to doing our part to control the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Until life goes back to normal, we will not be doing adoption events at PetSmart. Instead, we will be doing individual meetings by appointment and practicing social distancing at each meeting.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our online adoption application at www.uaaf.org. For more information, or to schedule an appointment, call/text Kirsty at (435) 671-0985, or email kirsty.ju@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Tuck 
Sex: Male
Age: 14 years 11 months old
Coat: Black and white, short coat
Weight: 62 lbs
Activity Level: Companion

Tuck is a loveable senior Border Collie Mix who is looking for his forever home. He loves walks more than anything and will even quickly trot to the door with his tail wagging high if he knows it’s time to go for a walk outside. Tuck enjoys cuddles, is as sweet as can be, and will be a wonderful companion. Being near his people is his favorite place to be. He would do best in a one-level home with someone who is home a majority of the time. He is schedule oriented but can also get used to a new schedule fairly easily. Tuck is so friendly to both people and dogs; he has never met a stranger. He is a homebody and would prefer not to travel too often.  

Tuck is healthy and has quite the energy for a dog his age. A couple of walks a day and love from the people around him will make him one happy dog! For a dog, a good life is important, a long one is not - they aren't counting days. Would you make the world a better place and provide a loving home for sweet Tuck?
Tuck is being fostered in Charlotte, NC. For more information on Tuck, contact his foster mom Emily at emilybrito1125@gmail.com.

Our adoption application can be found at https://cbcr.org/adoptionapp/.  If you have submitted an adoption application to CBCR within the last three years and you have not moved, please contact the foster parent before submitting another application.  The foster parent will let you know if another application is required.

Scotty is a 9-year-old likely Schnoodle who was starting to become aggressive with cats in  his home. He lost his doggie friend last year, she was an older and larger dog, and his behaviors changed after that. He seemed sad without his dog friend.  He can be dog reactive/aggressive when on a leash, so someone who can work with him on this will be helpful, and he needs a home with no small children or small pets, possibly as an only dog (or maybe with a larger older dog). Scotty is a big guy at about 33 lbs, but he’s incredibly sweet and knows a number of commands.  

Scotty is neutered, up to date on all vaccines, and microchipped. He will be having an anesthesia free dental on December 15 to get his teeth all spiffed up.  His adoption fee is $275.00. You can find the adoption application (required) here:

animal.description:
VALIUM - 2 years old, 71 pounds, friendly but may take a little time warming up to new people, pulls on the leash, good with dogs, likes to play with other dogs, may guard food from other dogs, best with older kids, no cats, very playful, hyper, can jump an 8 foot fence, very smart, can open doors, slightly food aggressive.

Valium is so excited to get out of that cage, he is all over the place! Trying to harness him was quite a sight I'm sure! Finally successful with the harnessing, we were off. Valium politely greeted every dog we passed in the kennel, even the ones who weren't so dog friendly. He pulled me down the hall and out the doors in what may have looked like a panic but it was only his eagerness to get out. Valium was hyper and jumpy in the yard. Going after my treat bag a few times I resorted to getting him into a sit, which he gladly did...but only for a moment so I'd grab a tennis ball and toss it. Valium is a big boy. He's strong and can also be demanding. He's looking for a new home. He'll need lots of daily exercise. He'll need lots of attention. I bet with plenty of this exercise and attention, Valium will be gladly at your side just chilling while watching your favorite baseball team knock it out of the park. Bring your dogs and kids in to meet Valium and let's see if we can all get along keeping in mind Val might guard his food or toys from other dogs so managing this behavior is vital to a successful integration. Keeping a close eye on everyone is important as Valium settles into his new home with his new family. Call the Virginia Beach Animal Care and Adoption Center (341 S Birdneck Road) at 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page to make an appointment.

animal.description:
Mr. Bean is a cute little black poodle who flew all the way from Texas to find a loving Colorado home. He was brought into the Texas shelter to be euthanized by a family that had owned him for 10 YEARS! We think he is about 12 years old and weighs in at about 12 pounds. He is an active, fun loving guy who would love a furever home with a nice big fenced-in backyard to run around in.  He likes people a lot and loves attention and getting petted. He would love a home where his people were around a lot. He can be a little bit of a resource guarder, so we are looking for a home with no young children or alpha dogs. Mr. Bean gets along with other dogs, but we would need to see how introductions go if he goes into a home with other pets.

When Mr. Bean first came into rescue he peed very slowly and for extended periods of time. Because he is a poodle, not a schnauzer, we didn't immediately think of bladder stones but that was it! He had 3 painful stones that were blocking his urethra. He had the stones removed, and had a significant dental, and has healed very well in his foster home. He will need to eat a special prescription food for life in order to help prevent a recurrence of the stones. Mr. Bean has been wearing a belly band in his foster home to prevent pee accidents, this could be the result of the damage from the stones still healing, or he may have never received really good potty training. He does not poop inside though, so there is hope. We will send belly bands to his new home which are an easy solution to this issue. ? 

Mr. Bean is neutered, up to date on all vaccines, and microchipped.  He also had the big dental and the bladder stones removed. His adoption fee is $225.00. You can find the adoption application (required) here: http://cominischnauzerrescue.com/forms/vintage-dog-rescue-adoption-application/

animal.description:
Enzo was born in 2013. He is bonded with Sophie and they are pretty much in separable. Enzo is a typical male chihuahua, he knows how to use a pee pad and will go outside in nice weather but he will mark if there are other male dogs in the home. For this reason he would do best in a home with just him and Sophie. He is the ultimate lapdog, and if your lap is occupied he will take a perch on your shoulder. Enzo prefers a quiet home with not a lot of visitors, he also does not prefer small children. Do you have a quiet home for Enzo and Sophie to live out their days?

Included with adoption: Age-appropriate vaccinations, up to date heart-worm preventative, heart-worm test if over 6 months, insurance for 30 days, microchip with registration, and spayed or neutered- if not already, a voucher is provided. 

If you are interested in adopting, please complete our Pre-application: https://form.jotform.us/asr628/ShortAdoptionInquiry

animal.description:
Pinky Pie was born on a property south of San Antonio. She was not socialized with people at all so it takes her some time to come around. She is very, very sweet and would do best in a home with other dogs. We would prefer a home with older kids just because screaming may scare her. 

She is 7-8 months old, good with dogs, cats and will most likely be okay with kids 
She is potty trained, kenneled trained but is still working on walking on a leash. That has been one thing that is taking her the most time to get used to because she is scared on walks. She does have some noise phobia and will freeze on walks if she gets startled.

We are working on sit and shake.    She loves shoes and socks so she will need to be monitored for the chewing. When she gets too scared she will nervous pee and she will poop on car rides.

*Because she missed her critical socialization period, it is safe to say that she will carry anxiety with her. So she may not be the dog that you take to the park or lake as she may get overwhelmed. Owners will need to be patient and continue to work on coping skills and calming skills so she can have confidence in new situations.

Pinkie Pie will need to go to a home with playful dogs. She functions best on a routine.

animal.description:
Hola! My name is Chulo. Did you know that’s Spanish for cute? I mean, just look at my pictures! My foster friends call me Chuey though. Don’t want to give me an ego I guess! 

Chulo/ Chuey is approximately 2 years old and about 80lbs. He is a fun-loving family member! He is guessed to be a husky/Labrador retriever mix with a fluffy, adorable tail. 
His loyalty and protection is matched by no other. He is a quick learner and highly intelligent which also means he is stubborn but submits with friendly reminders. He would love someone to help him combat his stranger danger fear once he’s comfortable in a place, yet, being properly introduced totally diverts any reaction and he truly just needs a responsible owner. 
He is house trained, loves walks, and is good in a crate alone. He loves relaxing in a kennel! 
He gets along great with his male Shi Tzu and female Rottweiler doggie roommates. He has been amazing with all dogs who have come his way! Felines are not friends though. 
He has been around toddlers and younger children and has been very curious but gentle.
He’s been patiently awaiting his furever home! Chuey is such a well behaved gentle giant who has been overlooked for far too long. He has amazing manners- no jumping, mourning, or accidents. He lives for belly rubs and will give you an occasional little kiss. He is a sweet, patient boy and ready to steal someone’s heart. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

For additional information see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Name: Bella & Nelly

Age: Bella - 3 years & Nelly -1.5 years

Current Weight: Bella - 50 pounds & Nelly - 55 pounds

Rescued from: Texas

Bella & Nelly was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. 

Meet Bella and Nelly, bonded pair. Nelly is Bella’s daughter from her first litter. They were owned but mostly kept outside until Bella got pregnant one more time. They were surrendered to the rescue to find a better life. Bella had her babies and took great care of them and has been reunited with her daughter Nelly. They are now ready to find a new family together. They are both so loving and grateful. They are very active, playful and love to give hugs. They are medium energy and are learning house manners but may jump out of excitement. Nelly is a bit shy at first but slowly warms up and will shower you with kisses. Bella is more outgoing and will love you the moment she meets you. They love treats and they sit to take them quite gently. They are crate trained and sometimes they like to switch crates with each other. They like laying on the couch and cuddling with their humans but also love being outdoors when it’s time to play, and they will go straight to the back door when they are ready to come back inside. They love benebones, bully sticks and any kinds of treats. They are both super smart and may have been cats in another life. Nelly can jump really high, so a tall fence is recommended in her new home. Bella likes to rub her body against her human’s legs when she’s looking for love and pets. They are great around men, women and children, and wonderful around other dogs. Bella is heartworm positive and going through slow kill heartworm treatment. Nelly is heartworm negative. Nelly and Bella are looking for an amazing family to love them forever.

Health: up to date on required vaccines

Adoption fee: $700

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

To apply to adopt Bella & Nelly, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Calling all Lab lovers! Meet Oliver! This 6 year old, middle-aged man has a wonderful calm demeanor and a penchant for sneaking snacks! Oliver is not a fan of cats or small dogs, but he is a loyal family dog who does great with kids. He's generally a very patient boy who enjoys pets and hugs from human kiddos and is known to keep guard sleeping right next their beds. Like all dogs, though, Oliver does have his boundaries and doesn't like to play rough. A short run or game of fetch with a Nerf football once in a while is more his speed of play. Oliver is not a big fan of being left alone in his kennel, but will gladly go with you wherever he's allowed to go - he's a great car rider! Oliver also knows how to sit, stay, come, lay down, and shake hands/paws. He's a very smart boy with great mature manners looking for the perfect home. Contact ARF with any questions or fill out an adoption application for Oliver today!

-----
IMPORTANT: To protect the health of our staff and volunteers, ARF is currently conducting adoptions by appointment only. Please see more information below.

-Contact Info:
Have questions first about the adoption process or a particular animal? Please click the Contact this Organization button.

-Ready to Adopt? Please visit www.animalrescuemobile.org to submit an adoption application, or click the Adopt Me button to request one via email.

-The Adoption Process:
An adoption application, veterinarian and/or personal reference, a home visit, and a $150 adoption fee are part of the process. All animals will be up to date on shots, microchipped, and spayed/neutered before adoption.

-Please Note:
Sponsors are needed to help ARF with the cost of vet care. If you would like to sponsor an ARF rescue, please click the Sponsor Me button. A sponsor donation of $50 will help cover the cost of a spay/neuter surgery. Plus, ARF is a non-profit organization and all donations are tax deductible.

animal.description:
Nikki is a 10-year-old Husky who came to HRA in January. Nikki was rescued from a hoarding situation and went through a rehabilitation program with the ASPCA. She was transferred after graduating to HRA. Since her time with HRA and myself, she's been a very shy gal and a bit on the skittish/jumpy side. It's necessary that you approach her slowly and quietly; therefore, she would do best in an adult only house (no apartments) that's quiet. 

She'd do best with someone that can spend time with her and help her keep to standard routines such as going for walk and going to the bathroom outside. She isn't demanding at all; in fact, she is very content to sleep in her crate most of the day. She does enjoy her walks taking in all the smells and scenery. I live in a two level home but she's not shown any interest in going upstairs or down to the basement. In the time with me, I feel she's become more relaxed and is learning to trust and feel comfortable with me. She's a beautiful girl, and, underneath her gorgeous coat, is a dear, sweet dog looking for a new chapter to her senior life. We are looking for a special home for Nikki because she has cancer.

At this time she is comfortable and happy and the oncologist believes Nikki may have a year of quality life to enjoy. Nikki would love a home where she can go on walks, enjoy life, and relax. Please let this last chapter be comforting, stimulating and positive. And if you adopt Nikki you will also receive a free painting of her because of how special she is!

I'd be very happy to share with you what I've learned in our time together. I can be contacted at epc31855@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Meet our beautiful Cowgirl, Belle Starr is a beautiful female Heeler mix of 3 years old and 35 lbs. Her face has a darling mask on it, so cute! Named after a famous cowgirl of the West, Belle is sure to be your best friend and companion for many sunsets over the range!

Belle is calm, quite, submissive, affectionate, friendly and easy going. She is very shy at first, but warms up quickly in the right environment. She lived in the country, on her own, for a few years, with other dogs (including her off spring), until we apprehended all of them in September. Now, she is ready to find a special place to call home.

Belle is a great eater and is crate trained. She is also house trained. She has lived with other dogs. A slow and methodical introduction to other dogs went well and she is co-habitating nicely in her foster home with other dogs. We think she would also do pretty well with a cat, if introduced slowly and appropriately too.

Belle has a gentle and sensitive spirit about her but as mentioned above, she is VERY shy and needs ample time with her new people to warm up to everything that will be new to her. If you aren't willing to be patient, she isn't the dog for you. If you are willing to be patient, she will be the best dog you have ever owned, trust us! She will do best in a home that is calm, without kids under the age of 12. 

She enjoys some tuff toys, nyla bones and loves a Kong filled with peanut butter and kibble. She will do best when fed her meals in a crate or baby gated from other dogs.

If you are interested in this dog, please contact volunteer Amy at amyh@rescuednready.com or at 918-688-0755. You can also fill out an application at www.rescuednready.com and send it to us for our review!

ADOPTIONS ONLY TO PEOPLE LIVING IN THE NORTHEASTERN OKLAHOMA AREA.  

The adoption fee is $225.00 and includes all current vaccinations, negative heartworm test, worming, microchip, and spay/neuter surgery.  Go to www.rescuednready.com to learn about our adoption process and download our application.  

CALL or EMAIL US TO MEET ONE OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS! Call Amy at 918-688-0755 or email at amyh@rescuednready.com.

animal.description: Princess is a 6-7yr old mixed breed of some sort (built, looks and acts like a cattle dog mix). She is now at an ideal weight of 40# and doing wonderfully. Princess is a miracle pup as she joined us when we were picking up some kittens from the local shelter and she had been found tied to a shelter fence - emaciated and with a huge mass on her neck. She was already spayed, clean and sweet - but very much scared and sick. Legally the shelter has to hold onto stray for a certain period of time in case someone is truly looking for them. We committed to hold onto her as a fospice for the weekend as the vet there said she had an "inoperable" mass and should be euthanized. Over the weekend, she was not well overall but still eating, drinking, loved toys and gave lots of kisses - by Monday we could not just hand her over and not try. We scheduled her for full work up (rads, lab work, etc) and got a second opinion. Just forward a month later - Princess had surgery and masses (2) were able to be fully removed. The biopsy did show adenocarcinoma of her thyroid but margins were good and all diagnostics showed no signs of spreading. Other than the large scar from her surgery, she is now unrecognizable and prognosis is amazingly good! It is very much possible that later the cancer pops back up elsewhere but all studies say that is usually years later, if so. She is very much full of life. Very sweet, perfectly housebroken, crate and leashed trained and loves to play. She is great with dogs and cats if properly introduced and the right match.

animal.description:
This beautiful babe is still searching for a forever of her own (its hard to believe, we know!). Kai is a 1 year old pointer mix, weighing in just around 40 lbs. She is a happy, energetic, and playful girl. Kai tends to be fairly calm inside the house (loves to lounge, loves her squeaky toys, and chewing on bones, etc.) but gets more excitable and energetic once she is outdoors. Similarly, during the day, she is wide awake and full of energy...while after supper she is ready to just settle in and snuggle/keep you warm. She LOVES to run, and is lightning fast! When outdoors, Kai is very focused on her surroundings and/or movement, such as wildlife and people + dogs walking by. Her foster family feels that she would do best in a home that has experience with a high energy pup like Kai. She is such a smart cookie; she knows how to sit, shake, stay, and does a good job of minding her manners. She is crate-trained and fully potty-trained. Kai has also spent some time with our amazing trainers at Fun Fur Pets, and below outlines further the ideal home environment to ensure that Kai (in all her energy!) is successful:

1 Kai needs a fenced-in yard (6ft+). 
2 Kai loves other dogs and loves to play with them, so any other dogs in the home should also love to play. She plays pretty rough, so will need dogs her size (40 lbs) or larger. She would also do just fine as an only dog! 
3 Kai needs a home with no kids (ages 16+ would be ok), as she has herding tendencies and will likely try to herd/chase them.
4 Kai needs a home without cats, chickens, or other small animals.

All in all, Kai is truly such a fun-loving, energetic, goofy girl, who has such a zest for life! More than anything, she just needs that perfect family who understands her and her needs. If you think thats you, please reach out to us (or complete an adoption application at https://newleashdogrescue.com) to learn more about adopting this beautiful girl! 

**Kais $200 adoption fee includes her spay, vaccinations, heartworm test, and microchip.
animal.name: Kai

animal.description: Mama J is a friendly, playful girl. She may be nervous when she first meets new people, but then she becomes their very comfortable best friend, so grateful to have their loving attention - and their cuddles. Mama is happy to be a best friend for people and other dogs. She adores the doggie companion in her foster home, and they are so affectionate to each other. She's also a calm, kind lady who loves playing with any toy and running in the backyard. She was an excellent mother to her litter of puppies, and now that they're off to new homes, she's ready to begin her training. She can do well on her leash walking, still pulling some and trying to run toward those squirrels and rabbits she sees. And she's making progress on answering to 'sit' and 'stay.' She's also house-trained and doing well in her pen, staying there when home alone. Mama J is a curious girl who's eager to learn and will do well in a family home. She'd especially love to go on frequent walks. She is heartworm positive, but all that means is that she'll need a couple of months of rest during treatment, at APA!'s expense. Come meet this adorable girl!

animal.description: Do you feel that there's a distinct lack of doggy kisses in your life? If so, Ella has got you covered! This energetic lady is most at home when she's climbing into your lap and showering you with kisses, and will happily follow you around the house to provide this service free of charge. Ella does understand the need for space though and will trot off to enjoy some of her other favorite pastimes if you're busy, such as chewing on squeaky toys, snoozing on the couch, or at your feet, or watching the squirrels in the backyard. Playing fetch is also a favorite of hers, and she enjoys long, quiet walks around the neighborhood. Her main goal in life, however, is definitely to be a master class snuggle buddy. And did we mention the kisses? In addition to being a nonstop love machine, Ella is house trained and does well when left home alone for short periods. She's working on her basic commands and walking skills and is proving to be a quick learner, partially due to being very treat- and affection-motivated - she already has 'sit' mostly down and is working on learning to hold the position for long amounts of time. Finding someone who is eager to help further her training would be absolutely wonderful for her! Loud noises and other dogs can still be a little much for her right now, however, so she would really flourish in a quiet home with active adults, preferably where she's the only dog while she works on her doggy socialization skills. So if you're looking for a being of pure energy and love packed into one wiggly little body, come meet Ella today!

animal.description: Candy is a very special lady who has had a tough life, but it has not let it get her down. She has to be one of the most loving dogs that her foster has ever been around. Her eyes follow you with a look of affection everywhere you go. I almost think she would trade food (which she adores) for getting her ears scratched! Candy has a fractured vertebra near her tail with spinal cord damage. She has some use of her left hind leg and is able to hop around and very limited, if any, use of her right hind leg. She can handle a single step from the house to the yard, but not more than one. She was not a fan of using a wheelchair, preferring to hop (sometimes with a good deal of speed)! She likes to go on short trips in the front yard to sniff at things (maybe a hundred feet in any direction). Candy also likes to snooze on her bed or lay in the sun outside. She's a very easygoing companion. Despite her injuries, Candy just loves her humans. She likes to follow her foster family around the house so she can be in the same room, and she loves to have her ears scratched. She is not very needy or pushy about getting attention, and will happily settle down to wait until you are ready. Candy lives with two pups in her foster home, one large and one small, and she has tried to play with them some, but she isn't too mobile due to her paralysis. They mostly hang out on dog beds together and watch for people jogging by when in the backyard. She has also interacted very well with a 6 year old child who understands that she is special. Candy is very interested in new people, likes to sniff and let them pet her. Candy does great when her humans are away, whether she is inside or outside of the crate. She will wait patiently by the door for her people to return. Candy does not have control of her bladder or stool due to her back injury. Her foster parents keep her in diapers when inside, and usually take them off when she goes outside. Candy is a smart lady who will follow commands when told to go inside/outside. She also understands when told to go to her 'pillow' (dog bed) or 'box' (crate). An ideal home for Candy would be one with no stairs, and with someone who is around to give her lots of pets and just hang out with, and someone who is patient with her toileting needs. Do you have the ability to take care of this sweet and loving special needs pup? Then come meet Candy today!
animal.name: Candy

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE:

- REQUIRES A HOME WITH FENCED YARD
- REQUIRES ANOTHER DOG IN THE HOME
- EXPECTED TO BE A LARGE DOG (estimated adult weight 50-70lbs)

NAME: CAROLE BRADSHAW

LITTER: CAROLE is part of the "TOP GUN" litter

AGE/GENDER: 6 MONTH OLD, FEMALE

BREED: HUSKY MIX

ADOPTION DONATION: $525.00

TEMPERAMENT: Playful and mischievous
HOUSE TRAINING: Not yet. She is a baby so she'll need a consistent schedule with multiple opportunities daily to go outside while she works on it. Puppies should not be considered reliable in regard to house training until 6-12 months of age. They're a lot like toddlers, who require diapers.
CRATE TRAINING: Good, she's young and trainable
OTHER DOGS: Good! She will need continued socialization, like all puppies. Another dog in the home is required as Huskies are very social breeds and can often get lonely without another companion. Dog companion must be medium to large size as Huskies do have a prey drive.
CATS: Would do best WITHOUT cats in the home.
CHILDREN: Dog-respectful children, 8 and older

HEALTH: CAROLE is healthy. She is altered, microchipped, flea treated, and dewormed. She has been given vaccination boosters in our care; however, adoptive families will be responsible for the remaining vaccinations that puppies need. Your adoption donation goes toward the cost of her vet care as well as transportation and general care costs.

HISTORY: CAROLE and her siblings came to us from Mexico where they were born under a car. Fortunately, they were found and saved. Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find them a great forever family and that is exactly what we plan to do.

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: CAROLE is a puppy so she's playful and has a lot of puppy energy. She is super cute and fun, but a lot of work. Her forever family should be committed to lots of training - obedience, house training, and socialization. This will ensure that CAROLE grows into a confident, well behaved adult. Puppies' personalities are dependent on their environment, and the structure and training they are given, in addition to socialization. Their personalities continue to grow and be shaped by their new adoptive families. Puppy daycare and socialization classes or puppy kindergarten are highly recommended for their personal development. She will more than reward you for all your hard work with lots of love, loyalty, and laughs.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and either a Martingale collar or a harness, depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO

Welcome to Motley Zoo Animal Rescue. We are a 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization that is run entirely by volunteers. Motley Zoo does not have a brick and mortar shelter location. Instead, all our rescue animals are cared for in private foster homes where the animals receive one-on-one care and attention in a home environment until permanent placement is found. Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application and we will work toward approving you as an adopter with our rescue so that we can set a time for you to meet!

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

animal.description:
This handsome lad is Tup!  He's a 4 year old Coonhound mix who weighs in at 52 pounds.  Tup may have been an outdoor dog for most of his life because he is much happier when he gets to go outside.  He'll need an owner with dog experience who can help him build his confidence inside the home, but also be willing to keep him active with outdoor activities.

Tup is a friendly, happy-go-lucky kind of guy.  He has a lot of energy and loves to play - especially with stuffed animals.  Tup carries them with him everywhere, walking proudly with his tail wagging the entire time!  He even picked out his own stuffed animal to bring with him to his first vet appointment!!

He loves car rides, but due to his energy one of his favorite volunteers recommends that he be crated for the ride.  Safety first!  Tup's friend walks him every weekend and she said his demeanor outside of the shelter is night and day from when they are inside.  Tup calms down tremendously once outside the building.  He walks calmly and then army crawls into her lap for cuddles when they stop for a break.  She said Tup is so loving and calm when he's in his element.  

Due to Tup's size and energy, we are requesting a home with no children under the age of 10 years old.  He can become mouthy and jumpy when he's anxious.  Again, he needs an adopter with dog experience who can help build his confidence and help him become the best version of himself.

Tup can't wait to find his perfect home and a buddy to take him on lots of walks and fun outdoor adventures!  If you think you can provide Tup with a great home, apply today!  He'll be sure to give you lots of love and laughter in return!! His minimum adoption fee is $275 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents.

He has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

animal.description: Beckham is an affectionate, energetic, and intelligent guy who excels at agility training, basic and complex commands, and lounging. Its hard to tell which he likes best solving puzzles, playing fetch and tug-of-war, or reclining on the couch with a chew toy. Beckham is considered special needs, behaviorally - he is very protective of his personal space, and will react if people get too close, or pet him for too long. Beckham needs a patient, devoted person who will earn his trust, and respect his boundaries. Animal Aid will provide free sessions with Beckham's certified fear free / positive reinforcement trainer to help that special person learn how to help this special dog. Potential adopter must have a securely fenced yard, and live in an adult-only household. Beckham is dog-selective; an introduction with your dog will be required. If you are interested in meeting Beckham, please contact our Training Coordinator at training@animalaidsociety.org * Will consider adopters outside of a 40 mile radius of the shelter.

animal.description:
Archie is a 2 year old GSD mix. He has a floppy ear that stands up when he is really interested in something (like a squirrel). He is quirky, funny and just a 78# love bug.
He is friendly with everyone he meets and generally all about the lovin and ear scratches and belly rubs. He is a  strong boy so can be a bit enthusiastic at times and needs some direction to calmly sit for attention. He does live in a foster home with 2 female GSD's. He plays rough and tumble with the younger GSD and will engage the older GSD when she lets him. He does need direction at times to not push play and he is learning this skill.  He can be picky about his "male dog" friends and also can be exuberant with meeting some dogs. This will need a strong leader, supervision and managing to insure he develops a positive relationship with other dogs in the home. He needs a home that will allow him time before introducing him to new dogs in the home. Archie due to size, strength and play style is not recommended for small dogs or cats. He is working on his doggy introductions skills so his future home would need to set him up for success by guidance and supervision. 
After a good walk and some play time he is content to lay at your feet and hang out. He is crate trained and housebroken. He has met children and been open and friendly with them but his size and strength is a consideration for very young children. Teenage children or older is recommended. He can be mouthy at times in play but very responsive to a simple "stop" in play and he gets the idea. He is learning good leash skills and basic sit and stay . He is strong and will test if his leader "means it" and so firm consistent direction is needed while on leash. He would benefit from continued training in basic obedience. He is very treat and food motivated. He loves toys of all kinds, especially  chew bones and "stuffies".  He truly is a pleasure to be around and a great companion. He loves to go on hikes, play in the yard and travels great in the car! This dog is the complete package!


***** Adoption Fee: $350 

 ***** NOTE to those viewing this profile on Petfinder.com: Visit our website for more information about our policies. Please ONLY sponsor or donate through our website at www.journeyhomegsd.org


 ***** View updates on Facebook at 
www.facebook.com/journeyhomegsd/

animal.description: Skye is a sweet 2 yr old spayed female who has been bounced around a lot. She will need somone who is willing to work with her on her issues.  She has food aggression with other dogs and is not a fan of small animals as she will go after them.  Her owner also states that she has separation anxiety and will poop in her crate when they leave every time. She is a typical Siberian who needs lots of exercise and mental stimulation. A tired dog is a good dog. She walks pretty well on a leash although she does pull, after all she's a Siberian. Skye also likes to play fetch, which is not typical for a Siberian. She plays well with other dogs her size or bigger but would require supervision with toys around other dogs. Skye would love a new stable home for the new year.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Skye also has food aggression with other dogs. She will either need a home without other dogs or an adopter who is willing and knowledgeable to work on this .

animal.description:
Pauly is a handsome 5 year old American Bulldog mix. He came to us after another rescue reached out to see if we could help after he had been passed up by adopters for years. 

Pauly is a very strong, but also puppy-like guy! He loves exploring & is very curious about everything in the world. When he’s not busy exploring, he loves curling up in one of his many different & quite humorous sleeping positions. 

He would benefit from an active home with previous bully breed experience. He would prefer a feline free, adult home. While he enjoys going on walks with other dogs, he would likely do best in the home as the only dog, but may be willing to share his home with a dog permitting a successful introduction! 

We would like to do a short foster-to-adopt trial for Pauly to make sure that the match is right for both him and his family.

To foster-to-adopt please fill out the form at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

PLEASE NOTE: To foster-to-adopt Pauly, you need to be a resident of Connecticut.

animal.description:
Chip an absolutely beautiful 15 month old bully breed mix who came into rescue after he was saved from a less than ideal situation. This poor boy has been through so much, between living in misery for almost the whole first year of his life, this boy had emergency surgery, that ultimately saved his life shortly after coming into rescue due to previous care before coming to us. 

After all of his hurdles, this boy is finally ready to start the life he so very much deserves. Chip is initially a bit shy around new people, but warms up very quickly! Once he’s comfortable this boy is fully of puppy energy! He would benefit from an active, bully breed savvy family, that can help burn off his energy.

Chip is a very smart boy, he knows sit, down, stay, & paw! He is also crate trained & house broken! Chip would love if his new family can continue to work on his training & exposing to him the outside world he finally getting to live in! He has a very sensitive side, so he needs a family who focuses on primarily positive reinforcement based training so he can continue to have exciting experiences! 

Chip is working on his manners around other dogs, he does well walking with them, but for now would likely do best as the only dog in the home. He is a bit too much for feline friends or small children! Chip would make an amazing addition to a home with older children or an adult home!

We would like to do a short foster-to-adopt placement for Chip to make sure he and his new family are the right match for each other.

To foster-to-adopt please fill out the application at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

PLEASE NOTE: To foster-to-adopt Chip you need to be a resident of Connecticut.

NOTE: Dori is now in the adoption room at the OKC Shelter! 
Dori is a special dog that needs a special kind of person. She didn't have the greatest start in life but she's ready for her restart! She may flinch if you are too quick with hand movements. Despite her past, Dori is still ready to love. Once she knows she's safe she is the sweetest, most loyal, playful little girl. She is HOUSEBROKEN, knows FETCH, walks well on a leash, and sleeps in a crate all night. She's a quiet dog. Due to her uncertainty of people at first, Dori needs a home with adults only (may be ok with older children (13+) that will respect her space and give her time to warm up to them). If you think you might be a good fit for Dori but aren't sure, ask about FLASH FOSTERING her before adopting her. You can take her home and see if she would be a good match. If you have any questions about Dori, feel free to reach out to (Karly), her former foster mom  kbootz44@aol.com


The dog/cat adoption fee, which is normally $60 unless we are having a special, includes spay or neuter, MICROCHIP, age-appropriate shots and health check. The shelter is at 2811 S.E. 29th St., phone # 297-3100. Use pet's ID # when inquiring. Special Adoption Fees: In the following cases, the adoption fee is $30-if more than one pet is adopted, if the pet is 4 years of age or older, if the pet has been in the adoption center more than 2 weeks, and if the pet is a 'special needs' pet.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi! My name is Tuck! I am a sweet and goofy 75 pound, two-and-a-half-year-old Dutch Shepherd mix. I enjoy playing with my foster siblings and would do well in a home with other large, energetic, playful dogs. I have not been around cats or children, but my foster parents believe I would do fine in a home with older children. I get very excited at times, so I would probably accidentally knock over the littles. When I'm not playing, I absolutely love to cuddle and will let you rub my ears for hours. I am mostly crate trained, but I can be pretty vocal when I'm ready to be let out. I can be trusted to roam free with my foster siblings, but have been caught pulling things off the coffee table. Oops. I have also chewed a hole in my foster dad's slipper. I was just trying to create some air flow, but he didn't appreciate the help. So now my foster family is teaching me what is and isn't acceptable behavior. I walk well on a leash and enjoy learning new commands. I have a beautiful brindle coat that has tendency to shed quite a bit, but that is the only mess I make inside since I am housebroken. I enjoy meeting new people, making new friends and going on adventures. I love car rides, but get nervous to actually get in the car. Hopefully with time I'll just jump right in! I am looking for a forever home with a patient family that loves to work on training, play and cuddle! I am recovering from heartworm treatment, so I won't be available until just after Thanksgiving. I am being fostered near Greensboro. If you would like to add me to your family, please contact your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please fill out an adoption application on our website: https://freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi! My name is Slye and I'm the sweetest (and handsomest) eight-year-old boy you'll ever meet!

I am friendly with people and small dogs and naturally prefer women. It's not that I don't like the big dogs, I do, I just prefer hanging around with the littles. I don't need to be the only man in your life, though, either. I'm good at sharing. I'm way too interested in cats and chickens so a home without them would be best.

I'm very affectionate and want all of the love you can give me. I'm also learning to play. I've discovered that I love Nylabones and other chew toys. I really like the plush toys, too, but I'll shred them pretty quickly. It's just so fun!

I'm crate trained and that's where I sleep when you aren't home. I'm also housebroken but still have accidents sometimes. My new foster family is diligently trying to teach me to walk appropriately on the leash. I was hit by a car in my younger days, so now I get pretty anxious when vehicles pass. I'm a work in progress, so my new family will have to continue teaching me leash manners.

If you would like to add me to your family, please contact your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please fill out an adoption application on our website:
https://freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org

I am being fostered in Kinston.

animal.description:
Medical note:  I am LYME positive and will need to be treated with antibiotics.  The humans can explain that to you.

Heeeey friends! My name is Patches and I’m seven years old and weigh 45lbs. I am a former hunting dog and I am just loving the retirement life. I can play, lay around, and follow my sniffer outside whenever I want - life is great. 

Living full time inside has me learning new manners. Who knew you were allowed to walk on living room tables? Bathroom manners are on point, though. 

My favorite place to hang out is my crate. I have tons of blankets, a pillow, and my hoard of stuffed animals. I can sleep for hours BUT when it’s time for the pack to go outside - count me in! I like to run and do zoomies and it’s a game to see who can run back inside the house the fastest. I ALWAYS win that game because I am FAST!  I also love to roll around in the grass and leaves on my back and do squiggle wiggles. I’m fun to be around and sweet as can be.

A yard with a six foot fence would be nice. It would keep me safe because although I may not want to, I could jump over a lower fence easy-peasy. I also am lightning fast to bolt for the front door as soon as it opens. Until I learn you’re the boss, you’ll want to keep an eye on me. I correct well in the meantime. I’m really a good girl, I just need to know the rules. 

Well, it’s been real nice chatting with you. I hope you stop by to meet me sometime soon. I had a great Christmas with my foster family but I am ready to start the new year with my new family!

Fun fact about Patches: we use the squirt bottle to correct undesired behaviors and the first time she was squirted, she looked at the ceiling like it was raining.

You can come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  On Saturday's from 2-4pm, the events are open to the public. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Medical notes: I am LYME and EHRLICHIA positive.  These can be treated with a 3-4 week course of the antibiotic called doxycycline.  The humans can give you all the details.

Hi my name is Justin, but my foster family calls me Beaufort or Beau! I haven’t really responded to any name yet. I’m 7 years old and 58 lbs! I was left to die all because I would not serve my owner's purpose: to hunt. Needless to say, my life has already gotten better. I'm all bundled up in my cozy sweater chewing a peanut butter bone and have decided to continue my career as a 'couch potato'.

I am an easy going guy. I love other dogs and attention from people and lots of snuggle time, but I also love alone time to do my life pondering and (nap). I am great in a crate and I lay quietly.  Sometimes I go in to lay down even when I don’t need to be in there. 

I think I would be a great coffee and newspaper reading buddy. I am not too much of an eager walker. I love the backyard at my foster family’s home. I enjoy exploring, running, and sniffing.' The other night I got spooked and jumped their 4 ft fence. I am home safe and sound now.  BUT because of this, IF you have a fence to let me out unleashed, ODHS would like it to be a 6ft fence to keep me safe.

I am fine with short walks but not really excited about long walks. I love car rides and I am almost positive I would like to stick my nose out the window, but it’s cold right now.

I am a little jumpy at loud noises but don’t care when the doorbell rings. I avoid furniture until I know I am invited. 

If you’re looking for a best buddy - THAT’s a job I would happily do. Come meet me soon.

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

He'd be happy to travel in the car with you as well

Even though he will play a bit of tug-o-war with you; he'd be just as happy relaxing next to you; high energy he is NOT!

He is a 5-yr old GENTLEman; 60lb male Boxer mix. He loves everyone he meets and is a quick to give you a little kiss! He has been good with older children and very polite with excellent manners. Goose does need to be the only dog.

As part of Goose's $250 adoption fee, he is neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccines, and current on his monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. animal.description:
Sad adoption return

Video link: https://youtu.be/ufMEcftyuu0

FOR ADOPTION! Note: Only those with a responsible dog ownership history and excellent vet reference need apply.

(For more pics, visit nr2r.petfinder.com or www.RoadtoRescueLA.org)

INSTRUCTIONS TO APPLY:

PLEASE read profile thoroughly BEFORE applying:

DOG APPLICATION LINK: http://www.roadtorescuela.org/dog-application

Makayla (female)

Original intake date: 6/9/2020

Adopted: 9/30/2020

Returned: 11/24/2020

Maltese/ Poodle mix

Approx 13 years old

6.10 pounds

Adoption fee: $waived to RESPONSIBLE pet owner

Good with other dogs: yes

Cats: yes

Vetting: altered (spayed/neutered), UTD on shots, heartworm negative, fecal negative, dental performed in June, groom done after she was returned (because she came back matted and unkept), on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped

Health issues: blind and deaf; seizures (from when she was adopted - skull fracture - read profile - on Phenobarbital)

Temperament: quiet, can get panicky if unfamiliar situations; when she's comfortable she will relax

Energy level: low once she's comfortable

Groom needs: High; requires regular professional grooming, along with intermittent brushing to avoid matting

Biography: Where do we start? We will start with when Makayla came to us. She came to us in June with a large infected injury on her back. She was found as a stray and we posted trying to find the owner but no one ever came forward. We had her vetted and the wound treated. Once the scabbing from the wound fell off we saw three puncture wounds which led us to believe that she was picked up by a likely a hawk or owl but she won that battle. She was with us for three months until what we thought was the perfect application came in. The applicant had been in rescue and also worked at a vet clinic. We felt confident Makayla would be cared for a loved for the rest of her life. About a month into the adoption we received a message from the adopter that Makayla had a seizure and was rushed to the ER (the adopter is not local). She messaged us asking if we'd ever seen her have a seizure before and we had not and advised her as such. We asked her to keep us posted and she did and Makayla was placed on seizure medication. Not more than a week later, we get a message she's having to move. Makayla gets returned and that is when we find out that Makayla didn't just start having seizures she fell off the bed and fractured her skull! We have ER vet records indicating as such. We understand that accidents happen but to give the impression that the seizures just started happening out of the blue is just wrong and especially for someone who works at a vet clinic and who was supposedly in rescue and then to return her is just plain cruel. We feel we failed her but we won't fail her again. Makayla is a sweet girl. If you watch her video you will see that she does bump into things. The video was taken in a place where she's not accustomed but she will learn her surroundings given time. She does use potty pads. She needs an understanding, caring and loving home who is willing to continue to manage her seizures with Phenobarbital and vet checkups as necessary. We realize she's elderly and now with a skull fracture and seizures, she may not live a long time but she has surprised us time and time again. PLEASE do not apply if you are not prepared for a blind and deaf dog. They take special care and time. We plan to make sure that this time her adoptive home will be her furever home.

**IMPORTANT NOTES**

*We do adopt out of state provided the adopter is willing and able to travel to us once approved. We do not ship or transport our animals and there is no exception to this rule.

*All of our adoptable dogs are small, and they are never to be left outside alone, ever! We only rehome our dogs to adopters that plan to have them as inside dogs and part of the family! We do allow adopters with doggie doors, provided there is SECURE fencing. There is no exception to this rule!

*NO SMALL CHILDREN!! As with almost all the dogs at NR2R, young children or a very active household is not recommended. Many of our dogs come to us BECAUSE of small children, thus we do not rehome our dogs to homes with babies or young children. KEEP THIS IN MIND IF YOU HAVE VISITING GRANDCHILDREN AS WELL! Even if the children are older, it would depend on the child AND the parent or parents.

*HOUSETRAINING: We do NOT guarantee that any of our adoptable dogs are housetrained. While most should be easily trained, keep in mind that they live in a rescue where they have access to the outdoors all day and are inside at night. Even if they were surrendered to us as housetrained, it doesn't mean they will automatically be housetrained in your home. Housetraining them should be easy in the right home with time, patience, and consistency.

*We do not guarantee the age, health or temperament of any of the dogs we rehome. Many of the dogs we take in come from animal control and rarely do we have histories and even when we do, many times the histories are inaccurate.

*Only adopters with a responsible dog ownership history and excellent vet reference need apply. If you bring this pet into your heart and home, you will receive in return many years of love, companionship, and loyalty. That's our guarantee.

Other notes: This pet is available for adoption through Ninna's Road to Rescue, Benton, La. We are 501c3 non-profit organization. Our mission is to rescue small-breed dogs and a handful of cats and to re-home them into RESPONSIBLE and CARING forever homes. DOG APPLICATION LINK: http://www.roadtorescuela.org/dog-application

Time may be of the essence if you are looking to adopt a specific animal. We do not reserve animals, unless and until we have approved your application, provided the animal is still available at the time we receive your application. The first APPROVED application we receive will be considered. We are NOT a first come, first serve rescue!! We adopt our rescues out to the RIGHT home, not just A home. Only responsible pet owners need apply.

Applying to adopt does NOT commit you to the adoption NOR does it guarantee the adoption.

CONTACT: Our adoptable pets are updated regularly, but if you want to check the availability of a pet... OR still have questions AFTER reading this profile, message us via our Facebook page. Please indicate the name when communicating with us.

www.RoadtoRescueLA.org

animal.description:
Seniors with spunk make some of the very BEST pets! Roscoe is a super sweet 13-year old hound mix. Look what Rosco has to say!

You'd never know it when you see me play! My foster siblings are teaching me how to play ball. We have lots of fun running around in the backyard. I love the fence, because I can roam and sniff as much as I want! I get along great with other dogs, so siblings would be great.

I was with my original person for 13 years, and it's easy to see I was well cared for. I love my foster mom and follow her everywhere. It's pretty clear I also really "dig" (get it - dog humor!!) couches and chairs. Did you say you want a lap dog? Heck, pick me...even though I may have a few extra pounds on me, I am great at snuggling. I am about 68 pounds of love!

I'm up to date on vaccines, dewormed and current on flea/tick prevention. My adoption fee is a bargain at $250! So please fill out the adoption form at http://pawsforlifenc.org/pet-adoptions/dog-adoptions/!

Please note that Rosco is a courtesy post and is available for adoption with Paws for Life NC.
