animal.description:
Straight out of the pages of a comic book, this guy is sure to make you laugh!  if ever a dog was made up of spare parts, it would be Bongo. His head is waaay to o big for his body, his legs are too short, and he;s perhaps, a bit bowl- legged but you can;t help but love him.  Those eyes will just melt your heart!  He's all about people and food, and if they come together that's even better! He came us as a stray from another shelter where he had arrived with a nasty skin infection and was very skinny. His hair is slowly growing back in and he is now at  a good weight, but these things take time. 

He really does enjoy his walks and would love a fenced yard to play ball in!

He loves large KONG Squeezz dumbbell, balls or ropes and will entertain himself for a good long time.  He would do well in a home with adults or older kids.  is fine on a leash when he sees other dogs on the street, but should be your only canine companion.  He really isn't into sharing his home with others. 

If you are interested in adopting him please call the Humane Society of Schuyler County 607-594-2255 ext. 201

Adoption Fee: $175  (dogs over 1 year) or $225 (dogs under 1 year) includes spay/neuter rabies, DHLPP and kennel cough vaccinations, worming, flea treatment, heartworm testing, heartworm preventative, microchipping and microchip registration fee. 

Due to Covid, we do not have open adoption hours. We are requesting that people fill out an adoption application first; then you can be pre-approved before your appointment. It does not obligate you to taking a dog. Details and applications can be found here: http://schuylerhumane.org/dog-adoption/

Visit us on line at www.schuylerhumane.org for additional information, an adoption application, to see more adoptable dogs and cats or for directions to our shelter.

animal.description:
Heidi has had a rough life. But she is a very forgiving dog. She has lived most of her life fending for herself on the streets of Sanford North Carolina. She has raised many litters and kept them safe. She was finally caught by somebody who gained her trust. She was placed into a foster home with her puppies. Her puppies have now all been weaned and Heidi is ready for her own home.

 She will bond closely with her human, has learned to love having pets and affection and wants to please her people . She will take treats very gently, give you her paw, hunt moles in the field and has figured out what a walk is and really enjoys those. she would do best in a home with somebody who truly wants a rescue dog in the truest sense . A quiet home with love and patience and not a lot of other animals or chaos would be best for her. It’s not that she’s bad it’s just that she still needs time to adjust to home life. She would do best with a fenced yard (must be over 4 ft so she can’t jump it. )

. Please apply at www.ittakesavillagerescue.com please be sure you’re on the North Carolina website not Delaware

animal.description:
FAST FACTS:
*3 Years Old - 55 pounds
*Very Shy - Quiet Home & Neighborhood Ideal
*Calm/Low Energy
*Dog Friendly - Calmer Dogs Preferred
*Older Children
*Potty/Crate Trained
*Training Required

BIO:
Greetings, future family! My name is Pretty Girl, and I am a special lady who needs a special person that will help me overcome my past and find my happy. Could that be you? I previously lived in a hoarding situation with 12 other dogs; I was bred and dumped at a shelter once I had my babies. As you can imagine, I am very shy and confused so I need a calm home where I will be given my own quiet space (maybe an extra bedroom?) to decompress and patient humans who will go slow with me so I can settle in and feel safe. I've learned in my foster home that I love lounging on the couch receiving as many cuddles as I can get, but still get overwhelmed by too much excitement so I think an adult-only home or home with older children who understand my shyness would be best for me. I am dog friendly, and would prefer any doggie pals in my forever home be calm and low energy like me. I'm potty and crate trained - I consider my crate my safe space and like having it as a place I can relax if I need a break - and would thrive with a family that will commit to signing me up for training so I can keep working on my confidence and blossom. I think training will be a great opportunity for us to strengthen our bond together, too!  If you think you could be the person to help me find my happily ever after, please fill out an application soon! 

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

animal.description:
Meet River, an approximately 2-year-old Pit Bull who has been a Misfit in May 2020.

This pet is neutered, up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heart-worm negative, and micro-chipped.

River has had a rough life.  He was found in an empty field and it took several weeks to catch him.

He has trust issues and takes a while to warm up to people. Once he is used to you he loves snuggles and lots of attention. He is not a fan of hyper kids running around him because that makes him very nervous. 

He cannot be around other dogs and would likely not be a good fit with cats, either. 

River is pretty low energy and will sleep most of the day right by your side. He does have a playful side and will play with toys. He is leash trained but when he is finished he will just plop down. He will cry when he needs to go outside and loves being outdoors.
  
River will take a while to decompress and will need a safe space in the house. 

Once he warms up he will transform into a squishy lovable beast.

You can apply to meet/adopt River at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application.

animal.description:
Jannero is a cuddle bug!  He’s an 85 lb, 3 year old, male boxer mix who has done FABULOUSLY in our Pups on Parole program.  He loves to meet new people. He does great with our lady dogs and with our altered males (we have a female in heat right now so the unaltered boys are a little on edge). Jannero walks great on leash, does well in his crate and kennel. He is house-trained and is not an indoor marker. Jannero’s  handler loves him and wants Jannero to find his FOREVER home. 
To get more information on a Pups On Parole dog, please contact a representative of the Lassen Humane Society at 530 251-7247 or e-mail ilovepopdogs@yahoo.com.  The Pups On Parole Program started in June of 2007 to help give homeless dogs a second chance at finding an adoptive family.  All dogs in the program spent time in our local county shelter, surrendered by their owners or picked up as strays and waiting for their owners to redeem them or to be adopted by new families.   The selected dogs are brought current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered if necessary, micro chipped, and heart worm tested.  They then are taken to the California Correctional Center Firehouse where they are assigned to a trainer/ inmate fire fighter.  These trainers groom and work with each dog and give them the extra time and attention they need to become wonderful family companions.   Most graduates are house trained and know basic obedience commands.  As of December 2018, 535 dogs have been adopted through this program.  To meet any of the Pups On Parole dogs, arrangements must be made in advance.

animal.description:
Dasher came into our care as a young puppy with his mother and siblings, and was adopted out almost one year ago. At some point during his puppyhood he developed a sense of "stranger danger," and he was returned to us as his adopter didn't feel equipped to handle this. 

Dasher has a heart as big as his derpy head and that long tongue of his! He loves his friends immensely. When you are in his "circle of trust," it's a great place to be! Dasher has lots of human friends. Making new friends takes time though, which slows down Dasher's adoption options. The company of other dogs, slow introductions with new humans, and pack walks have been great confidence boosters for Dasher, and he's enjoying the perks of hot dogs that come along with his training, when meeting new people. 

The perfect foster or adoptive home for Dasher would be outside of the hustle and bustle of city life. A yard where he can stretch his long legs, a canine sibling or two, and dog savvy humans who understand patience and positive reinforcement training are all things on Dasher's wish list, this holiday season.

Dasher is fully potty trained, neutered, and up to date on his vaccines. If Dasher sounds like a match for your pack apply today at http://www.aliverescue.org/adoption-application

Meet Bane! Bane is a gorgeous Rottweiler who tips the scales at 82 pounds. He's considered a med-high energy dog and is very food motivated which can make training easier. He also loves snooping around in the snow and may benefit from doing scent work training in his permanent home! He already knows the 'sit' and 'paw' commands.

You can also watch for stories, pictures, and videos about Bane on JR's Pups-N-Stuff's Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/. Ask to meet me today!!

Bane is a gorgeous 1+ yr old Rottweiler mix who weighs about 82 lbs. He's considered a med-high energy dog and is very food motivated which can make training easier. He also loves snooping around in the snow and may benefit from doing scent work training in his permanent home! He has a dominant personality and would do best in a home with either older kids or adults only. He knows the 'sit' and 'paw' commands.
 
Adoption fee: $600

Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.

animal.description: Sierra is a typical hound dog. She LOVES to play fetch with a tennis ball. She loves to run so definitely needs an active owner and a fenced in yard. We had her outside with Felix and they did great together. She was adopted and returned for not being so great with cats. She also is a resource guarder with items. In the home she resource guarded the adult from the kids. So at this time we will say no cats and no kids. She is also protective of her toys/bowls, but as long as her human is aware of that it shouldn't be a problem. For instance with Felix, she did not want to share the tennis ball. She was not aggressive about it, but she was very vocal and let him know with body language she wasn't sharing that. We would also suggest that if in a home with other dogs, to feed them in separate rooms. it really is very easy to work around. And she can be trained as she loves to watch/listen to humans. She is 4 years old and around 50 lbs. Sierra is spayed and up to date on vaccines & dewormer and microchipped. She will be $125 to adopt. Meet and greets by appointment only with an approved application. http://www.hshcwv.org/wanting-to-adopt.html

animal.description:
Ruby is an 8 year old pocket pittie who is one of the most sweet and loving dogs you'll ever meet. She can be a little shy when approaching new people, but she loves everyone she meets and is always looking for pets! Her favorite things to do are cuddling up next to you for a nap, getting belly rubs, and giving kisses. She is also great with other dogs and loves to play, wrestle, and chase. She would love to be in a home with another playful dog because she really came out of her shell after playing with another dog in her foster home. She gets overly excited around cats, so she may be good for a home with a young, playful cat that likes dogs or no cats at all. She is house trained, food motivated, walks great on a harness, and has great manners. She loves to follow her humans around like a shadow so she would be best for someone who is home more than not.

If you are interested in adopting Ruby, please fill out an application at:
https://www.dogsaredeservingrescue.com/adoptable-dogs/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Well, hello there! The name's Samson. As you can see, I'm a pretty handsome guy. These good looks haven't helped me find my perfect match quite yet, so I'm trying to be as patient as possible while I wait. I know the right family is out there for me, and hopefully, they're reading this right now. 

I'm a very lovable guy and I promise I'll keep you safe and give your love back a thousandfold. I enjoy getting attention from my people, and I also like to stay active. I do best with a nice routine as I tend to get bored easily. I think kids are great and I know we would have a blast playing together. However, I would like to be the only pet in the home; I want to be your one and only fur-baby. 

My one Christmas wish is for my forever family to find me... I hope it happens soon. Wherever you are, I'll be here waiting for you.
.
.

animal.description:
Anna is being fostered in WI. 

Here is what Anna's foster mom has to say about her:
Anna is a survivor! She was on death’s door at a shelter in Louisiana when Blind Dog Rescue Alliance stepped up to rescue her. She was found as a stray, shut down, emaciated, blind, and thought to be deaf (see attached photo of her at the shelter). When she arrived at her foster home she was quickly seen by a vet, and diagnosed with advanced Diabetes, which probably took her sight. She was started on Insulin, and has gone from 9lbs to 13lbs in two months. She is good about getting her injections, but because it has been painful for her on occasion, I slip a muzzle on her just before giving her injection. Her teeth are good, and other than her diabetes, she is in good health, so my vet estimated her to be eight years of age at most, probably younger. Anna is now a sassy, delightful, happy little girl with excellent hearing!
Anna loves her meals and her treats, wagging her tail like crazy in anticipation, and she always follows me around, in case it’s time to eat. She is quiet unless she hears someone entering her home, or when another dog barks. With a slow introduction she is good with other small dogs, although can be bossy. She would be fine as an only dog, although has been fine left alone with my other small dogs, I just have to tell her “NO” when she thinks it’s time to boss them around. She sleeps in bed with me and my other dogs. Anna gets around just fine as soon as she acclimates to her surroundings.
Because of her diabetes, she needs to pee more often, although that is getting better and better. She knows that she should potty outside, but if she doesn’t have a chance to get out, she is very good about peeing on potty pads, so I haven’t used diapers with her.
She will need to continue to have her diabetes monitored, but has been pretty stable on the insulin dose she is currently receiving twice per day. Her weight is good at 13 lbs, although another pound would be fine.
Anna is an unusual looking, pretty girl. She is petite with long legs, and her coat has become quite shiny. The only breed that I think of when I look at her is a Min-Pin, mixed with who knows what else.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.
animal.name: Anna: pretty girl (WI)

He's a mellow, sweet senior gentle dog with an easy-going, loving personality. We rescued him from the Downey shelter where he had been surrendered because his former owners were moving. Fender is house-trained, crate-trained, neutered, microchipped and current on vaccinations. If you are in the Los Angeles area and would like to meet FENDER please fill out an application at www.downtowndogrescue.org/adoption-questionnaire

animal.description:
Hadley is a sweet little girl that had a rough start in life. She wants so much to be loved but is very afraid of touch. Hadley is good with females but afraid of males. She lives with both in her current foster home and did warm up to the male in the house after a couple of weeks. Until then she barked as ferociously as a 15 pound dog can, pretending she would bite but never did. Hadley gets very excited when her foster mom comes home and wiggles like crazy. She will run over and lick fingers and allow brief scratching under the chin, but petting is still too much for her. Hadley loves to play with the other dogs in her foster home, even the 100 pounder. She needs a home with another dog to help her be brave and a securely fenced yard to keep her safe. A quiet home without a lot of comings and goings is essential and an adult home would be best. Hadley lives with cats and doesn’t bother them if they don’t react to her. No shared walls as she will bark at noises. Hadley is crated overnight but would probably do well sleeping on a dog bed in the bedroom, and at some point might like to share the bed with her person. She does need to be crated when alone as she will chew if left unattended for long periods of time. What Hadley needs most is someone patient enough to wait for her to share all of the love she has to give. Please email Katie @ kladams4545@gmail.com to check availability, but be prepared to complete the adoption application on Homeward Bound Dog Rescue MN website, Dogs Available for Adoption as well.
Requirements: Physically fenced yard, another dog, patient adopter willing to give time and space for a shy dog

animal.description:
Liv is an active, intelligent, attention seeking and outgoing Frenchie who can also be timid and nervous around new people in her home. When Liv isn’t chewing on her favorite buffalo horn or nylabone you can find her requesting some chill time and a good snuggle with her beloved humans.  After a cuddle session, Liv slowly searches for a bouncy ball to gently play with.  Liv loves plush toys but unfortunately cannot have them as she decides the inside stuffing is more enjoyable than the actual toy.  Oh Liv!  Even if she is closely watched, she still finds a way to ingest the stuffing. Her playtime is limited as she has been recently diagnosed with IVDD.  Liv often has one speed and can turn a gentle play session into one that is too active for her back issues therefore her playtime should be closely monitored and limited (more info can be found in the medical part of the BIO).  One minute she is super playful and the next she is ready to chill.  During her chill time, you can find Liv being extra lazy (typical frenchie) and will grab a comfy spot on one of her many beds to take a much desired snooze.  
Liv resource guards her humans and her home but not her food/food bowls or toys.  She attended formal training to help with her resource guarding but it is a constant work in progress.  Liv is currently living as an only dog and will need to remain as an only dog.  She was unable to play "nice" in her previous home. As mentioned, she guards her humans and has a bite history.  She has two bites on record both because Liv was guarding her home and her space.  She shows aggression only in her home and around her people (she views this as high value).  She is not fond of children. From observing her behavior, we believe it’s because they are too quick with their movements for her. Although her aggression seems to only be in her home, for Liv’s safety and the safety of others in the home we suggest she is the only animal in the home.  
Because Liv loves positive attention, can be lovable and responsive to her favorite treats we believe with the proper structure, a family that can offer firm leadership, be consistent in their efforts, patient and willing to work on proper dog behaviors we believe Liv’s behavioral issues can be worked through if her triggers are kept at a minimum.  In addition, being the only pet will help remove the triggers Liv has with resource guarding.  Liv gets timid and nervous around new people in her home as she is protecting her space.  Her foster family believes she would be best in a home with dog-savvy, gentle, teenage children or older AND in a home as the ONLY pet.  As with all of our dogs, we recommend slow introductions AND supervision around children when introducing a new dog in your home to make sure both she and they are kept safe.

Ducky came to The Animal Care Society after being transferred from a rural shelter. She had a pretty severe case of mange, but that has all been treated, we are just waiting for her hair to fully grow back in. Luckily, she is spending her time having fun in foster care until she can find her forever home. According to her foster mom, Ducky would thrive being in the home with another dog, particularly a male dog, so we are requiring her to be adopted into a home with another canine friend. She also does not mind cats. She is still working on housebreaking and isn't a huge fan of the crate yet. She can get a little nippy when she's excited, so she shouldn't go to a home with small children. Ducky would benefit from an owner that is willing to work with her on basic obedience training. She is also a very active girl, possibly even part herding breed. She would do well with someone who has a large fenced yard or goes on frequent walks. She would not be a good fit for an apartment.
If you are interested in meeting Ducky, head over to our website at www.animalcaresociety.org to fill out an application! \\\ DUCKY IS SPONSORED BY OUR FRIENDS AT OLDFATHER LAW FIRM THRU APRIL 2021! /// DUCKY IS SPONSORED BY OUR FRIEND LAURA EDELEN THRU DECEMBER 2021!

animal.description:
Obie is a great dog who is happy, loving, and playful.  Of course, he is a Bulldog so he also enjoys lounging and being lazy too! Obie loves attention from his trusted humans and enjoys playing with his beloved Jollyballs when he is in a playful mood. 
 When he plays (and while he doesn't mean it in an aggressive way when he is playing) he does sound a little ferocious and loves to growl quite loudly while he (literally) prances around and tosses his ball around the room. He has an adorable little prance that he does when he is happy and/or excited.  For him, "a tired dog is a happy dog" would likely be his best course of action for success in his adoptive home.  
When he isn't playing, he is content to lay on his dog bed next to the couch and suckle on a stuffed toy and snooze. He is not allowed up on furniture in his foster home and should never be allowed to be in an elevated position (up on a couch, bed, chair, ottoman, etc.).  Obie is likely not a dog that one will be able to snuggle on the couch or in bed with. However, he is just as happy being near his people, getting head scratches and hanging out with them. 
He will occasionally resource guard his ball a bit around other dogs if they are attempting to steal it away but overall plays "keep away" pretty well with the other dogs in his foster home for the most part.  They are always monitored to ensure one isn't stealing the others toys and are being respectful of each other during playtime.  
While Obie doesn't mind the company of other dogs and playing with them from time to time, he does best with easy going dogs who will not try to bully him or start fights with him.  He typically does not ever start a fight, but he *will* retaliate and stand up for himself if another dog tries to pick on him and/or bully him.  
Obie does have aggressive outbursts from time to time and those are likely linked to neurological issue that he has had since puppyhood.  He was attacked by another dog and shaken when he was very young so while he gets around just fine and can walk and run just like any other normal dog, he does walk slightly off kilter with a sort of "swagger".  His "swagger" is sometimes more prominent than other times, but it is especially noticeable when he is upset and/or his excitement level is too high.  
Obie is ultimately an insecure dog that needs to find a home that is quiet and easy going with a family that will provide calm, firm, and consistent leadership for him.  He absolutely needs a family who is very dog experienced, can be diligent and consistent in paying attention to and reading his body language and who is able and willing to deal with any issues as they arise. He does best with calm, firm and consistent leadership because he can then trust and rely on his people to provide him with a safe and secure environment.  It did take Obie time to learn to trust his foster family and, initially, he was quite leery and standoffish with them. This should also be expected in his adoptive home until he has been given time to be able to build a relationship with his new family members and has learned that he can trust them.  
Obie sometimes zones out and "sees red" and displays aggression toward the humans in his home when something occurs that upsets him, most typically when he is asked to do something he does not want to do or if something occurs that makes him feel insecure.  
Obie has bitten and has drawn blood in the past. It should be noted that if he is able to make contact, he bites with a determined bite each and every time.  After he calms down a bit, he does seem to have learned his aggressive behaviors are not acceptable in his current foster home and he typically will put himself in a time out in his kennel as his foster family has trained him to do.  If he doesn't start heading toward his kennel on his own, his foster family will firmly tell him to "go to bed" (and point toward his kennel) in which he will then typically go to his kennel.  He should never be given additional attention in these situations and should be largely ignored while being kenneled in a separate area (with the kennel door secured) for a time out/cool off period of at *least* 30-45 mins.  
While he does not enjoy it, Obie is muzzled when he is given a bath and/or his ears are cleaned and/or his nails are trimmed.  Obie is very food/treat motivated and will allow his muzzle to be put on him with the bribe of yummy treats.  When placing his muzzle, diligence and caution must be taken.  Any type of grooming interaction that makes him uncomfortable and insecure feeling (which, to date, we have experienced is all of them), he will begin displaying aggressive tendencies.  The muzzle will protect his people so that he can have necessary care routines accomplished without the danger of being bitten.  Again, if he is given the opportunity, he WILL bite when he is feeling insecure, scared or uncomfortable if precautions are not taken in advance to avoid such instances.  
Obie is always fed in his kennel to avoid food aggression issues.  He is asked to sit and and wait calmly in his kennel and then his food can be placed inside of his kennel without issue. His food bowl is not removed from his kennel until he is out of his kennel.  Again, he MUST have a calm, firm and consistent leadership in his adoptive home, just as he does with his foster family.  
With calm, firm and consistent leadership he seems to do very well and his outbursts are only occasional (and now that they know him well, can usually be expected and predicted) with with his foster family.  Due to his bite history, Obie will not be able to be adopted to any home with children under the age of 16 years old.

animal.description:
Hootie was born on October 2nd. He is a Border Collie and Catalouhla Leperard Hound mix that comes to us all the way from Dallas, TX. He has a rare skin condition and someone was trying to give him away in a Wal-Mart parking lot. Luckily, a good samaritan stepped in before he ended up in the wrong hands and he can now get the care and love he deserves. 

Hootie has a rare form of Epidermolysis bullosa acquista. This is an autoimmune disease that affects the skin, causing it to blister and scab over. He has been responding well to his treatments. He will require daily steroids, a weekly bath, and monitoring to keep an eye for flare-ups or need for medication adjustments. He will need to be seen by a dermatologist as a primary care vet cannot treat this condition. 

The adoption fee includes spay/neuter, age-appropriate vaccinations, and micro-chipping. If you are interested in adopting any of the sweet babies please complete our adoption application at www.erinregananimalsanctuary.com

animal.description:
If youre looking for the perfect sweet, lazy, cuddle-up-on-the-couch-with-you dog: youve found him! Dewey is a 2 year old Double Merle Aussie mix. He is completely deaf and partially blind, but he doesnt let that bring him down. He is extremely smart and picks up new training cues quickly. He is such a sweetheart and will sit in your lap for hours and get love if you let him. Dewey definitely has some separation anxiety (we get it, its scary when you cant hear anything!), so he would do best in a home with someone who is home often. Dewey likes to play every once in a while, but is pretty lazy and sleepy overall. He would do well in a home with another doggy friend to show him the ropes, but probably wouldnt do too well with high-energy dogs because he startles easily. He does also try to herd his foster sister a lot. Dewey really seems to be afraid of leashes for some reason - hell let you put it on, but will just pancake and not walk anywhere - so he would also do best in a home with a fenced in area (even a small one) for him to go potty. He is crate trained, but has never showed interest in any destructive behaviors at his foster moms house, so he could likely be given free reign of the house if you prefer. Overall, Dewey is a happy camper if he has love, hot dogs, and a comfy bed to lay on. He cant wait to meet you!

 Apply at www.lolasrescue.com

animal.description:
This cuddly dog has the most expressive face you've ever seen.

She excels at snuggles - all she's never wanted in life is to sit on the couch curled up next to her humans. She'll often plop herself into your lap, even if she doesn't quite fit - or at least scoot her butt right next to you.

Gaby is a six-year-old pittie who loves people (but not other dogs). She's calm, smart, and picks up tricks quickly once she understands what you want her to do - she knows sit, touch, shake, high five, nod, shake head, stay, and has good table manners. She's also crate-trained and housebroken, though she sometimes has accidents. When she's met kids in passing, she's been very patient.

Gaby is comfortable and relaxed in the house, but does not love walks - she'd be happiest in a private yard where she doesn't have to process constant changes in her environment. She's also a great dog for night owls - she naturally wants to sleep until around 2pm!

Gaby has cancer, but she's vibrant and has a lot of life in her. Give this good girl a home!

If you are interested in Gaby, please fill out an application at: https://www.dogsaredeservingrescue.com/adoptable-dogs/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Meet Woody and Jessy!! The bonded pair, Woody and Jessy, were rescued by a local lady who also kept their mom for 7 years. Sadly, their owners relocated and could not take the 2 younger dogs with them. Woody and Jessy weigh about 60lbs and are now 8.5 yrs young and have calm and gentle temperaments. They are house trained, and enjoy being around their people, but would do best with older children around 10 and up. They get along with other dogs, but young and/or rambunctious ones are too much for them. The city life and noises are overwhelming to these country gals, and they need soft guidance while on walks. Jessy is still a little unsure of the car rides but slowly getting used to it. Woody doesn’t mind being in a at all. An ideal home for Woody and Jessy would be a quieter household where their people are around more often than not, has a secure fenced yard, and if any kids or animals are present, they need to be respectful and give them the time and space they need as they settle into their new normal. They would do better in a home located in a quiet town/neighborhood removed from the hustle and bustle of urban life. Woody and Jessy were rescued from Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, and are being fostered in Portland, OR. Will you be their hero?
If you are interested in adopting Woody and Jessy, first step is to fill out the adoption application at www.streetdoghero.org/forms

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Lowen, please email amanda.thompson@lostdogrescue.org

Are you single?
Looking for someone who will always listen, but never talk back?
Someone who can be just as good of a hiking buddy as he is a couch potato?
Someone who will always wash the dishes without being asked?
Well, we've searched high and low to find you the perfect match. 
Swipe right and say hi to Lowen. 

At just over two years old, Lowen is an active pup that embodies Rottie joy and goofiness. He has melted the hearts of everyone he has met and has made quite a few four-legged girlfriends with his handsome looks and undeniable personality. Nothing makes Lowen happier than being with his one-and-only person (single occupancy household or experienced adult couple). While he takes some time to warm up to new people, once he's decided that you're his person, prepare yourself for endless love, laughs, and licks. Lowen is proud to be a stage-five clinger (bonus points if you know the movie reference) and will gladly join his human for outdoor adventures or use you as his personal pillow for a Netflix marathon. No apartments, please.

For Lowen, the world can still be a scary place as he discovers all of its sights, sounds, and smells so he would love to find an active and dog-savvy single adult (not a first time dog owner as an adult) who can give him an extra boost of confidence to really come out of his shell. Despite his shyness, he is also quite the ladies man and would do well with a calm and confident female dog sibling to race around with in the yard and show him the ropes from a dog's point of view. When he's not outside, Lowen is happy to lay by your side for all the belly rubs you have to offer. He also loves any and all treats and will politely sit for them and take them gently from your hand. 

So if you're looking for a pawtner in crime for daytime adventures and evening show binging, then Lowen is your man!

Estimated DOB: 6/22/2018

Sponsored by Leonard Gentile

Hi, my name is Den. People also know me as Sir Wiggle Butt because my whole body wags when I get to hang out with the humans. I absolutely love them all so much! I am a young dog, I am not too big, and I have oodles of the very desirable personality trait of being extremely attentive to my humans. That means I look to them for guidance, I learn quickly and I just want to please. Oh, how happy I would be to find the home that has the time to give me all the love and training that a young boy like me will thrive on. I have already started with learning good dog manners. I walk well on a leash, and I even like to heal beside you when walking off leash. Thats because my favourite pastime is to be close to my humans. Because I have not been socialised with other dogs, I act a little silly around them and I am not welcoming. However, I am still just a young boy and it is most likely that I could learn to accept and enjoy canine friends if you know how to teach me how. Or maybe I could just be your one and only?
Applications are open for a lucky family to adopt this sweet bundle of love. Den is a good boy with a lot of love to give and is eager to find his forever family that have all that love to give back in return, as well as the time and commitment to provide both the physical and mental exercise that a young dog like Den needs.

animal.description:
Kevin (Titus) is a goofy dog full of personality that will keep you smiling. There's never a dull moment when he's around. He's very playful and so eager to please. He wants to be right next to his humans. He loves playing fetch, going for walks (although he needs a bit more leash training), playing with tough rope and squeaker toys, and snuggling under the blankets. He's an incredibly smart dog and picks up on training quickly.

Kevin is potty-trained but sometimes has accidents when he's really scared. He's a bit fearful of cars and strangers (which makes sense since he lived on the streets for a bit before landing in a shelter) but distracting him with treats usually keeps him calm. He's picked up on a lot of new tricks including sit, down, wait, watch, leave it, and come. He has a lot of potential for more training because he's so smart.

He doesn't like cats and would do best in a home where he's the only dog. (Ok with larger/active dogs.?) He should be in a home with no small kids, as he doesn't have patience for the noise and chaos kids bring, and he's not very aware of his surroundings and can easily knock little ones over. He does well with older kids!

To apply for him please go to www.tothemoonandbackrescue.com and fill out the adoption application. Fee is 250.00 and includes Neuter, current on vaccines, dewormer, heartworm preventative, flea and tick preventative and microchipped

He loves playing with his foster siblings so a younger, playful, female dog would be good for him. Completed applications will be given to the foster to coordinate meetings as everyone feels comfortable.  This application helps us get to know you and your family a little better so we can find the perfect match! Application are found here:

animal.description:
This amazing little guy is Frankie....6 lbs Yorkie/Chihuahua mix

!!!!!! SPECIAL NEEDS !!!!!!


Frankie was initially found as a stray and impounded at a kill shelter. He was in rough shape. Hair loss, goopy eyes, skinny... not a good look for an older little guy.
We think Frankie is about 8nyears old.
He got adopted but with heavy heart FRANKY got returned to us after 10 days with his potential family. 95% of the time Franky was the perfect little dog but he randomly snapped at hands often unprovoked and with having children and their friends come to visit often this was just not the right home for Franky. 
He is again looking for a home with no kids and someone able to handle is attitude moments.

Frankie has a heart murmur grade 3 and is now on medication. 
It doesn't slow him down and he most likely will have plenty of years left but medication is required.

Frankie would love to have a safe home where he can lay his head and go for fun walks
This little guy is the sweet and so funny and playful still.

If you would like to meet Frankie please send us a message in order to receive an application.

His adoption fee is $ 250 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test, neuter, micro chip and a full refill of his medication

animal.description: So, so, sweet is this gentle old man.  Maxx was found as a stray, wandering aimlessly in the streets of Phoenix.  He ended up at or county shelter and  his prognosis of being rescued had timed out.  It was at that time when we became aware of Maxx and we took him under our wings.   We knew Maxx was an old man but were were taken aback by just how much he was sufferings medically.   Maxx had two GIGANTIC tumors on his penis.  They were infected and bleed often.  He also had a bronchitis and tested positive for tick fever.....oh.....and his eyes.  He is virtually blind in one eye and has partial vision out of the other.  Words can not express how wonderful it is to see Maxx feel better and finally beginning to live his life.  The bronchitis and tick fever is in the past and he has recovered beautifully from his surgery.  Maxx is a new kid!!  We are able to walk him (his favorite thing to do) about 40 minutes a day.  He loves all people he meets and is totally indifferent to other dogs, however he will need to go to cat-free home.  It is as though Maxx lived on a concrete slab his whole life, outside alone.  He is so grateful for what he has now.   Maxx loves tennis ball too!  He will walk around with one in his mouth and chase one down! Just feeling well has brought him back to life.  We love Maxx and are really to find him a home that will tend to his needs and let him live out his remaining time so, so spoiled.  If you are interested in adoption Maxx ($100 donation), please take a moment to fill out an application.  All adoptions start with an application, https://www.povertyspets.org/adoption-form.  Once received, you will be contacted within 48-72 hours.  Thank you!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Ruffles, part of the Ralphie and Ruffles duo!  We were rescued from a hoarding situation and have now made it to SCP to help us find our forever home.  We are both couch potatoes extraordinaire but also enjoy leisurely walks around the neighborhood.  We've been together thru thick and thin, so we really need to stay together - I'm Ralphie's eyes and ears.  We're dog friendly.  No cats please.  We haven't been tested around kids, but would probably do fine with less active kids who enjoy our slow, leisurely pace.  We're doing fine with our house training.  We are crate trained but are not using a crate since we love to lay together on our dog bed - there just isn't a need for a crate.  Our foster says we are really a pair of sweethearts looking for someone to snuggle with and who enjoys stopping to smell the flowers along the way.  If you are interested in us, please send an email to scpdogworld@gmail.com to get more information on how to fill out an application and have a great meet and greet to see if we are a match made in heaven.

Adopter for this dog must reside in the immediate Houston/Galveston area and be at least 25 years old.  A home visit may be required prior to this dog going to any home. The adoption fee for this duo is $190 (two for the price of one) which includes State of Texas sales tax. All dogs are microchipped, on heartworm protection, spayed/neutered, vaccinated, de-wormed and treated for fleas.

animal.description:
UPDATE 12-27-20 We had a trainer come and work with Nellie J. What a difference it has made just in 90 minutes! She is destined to be a wonderful family member! Her foster is going to continue with what trainer has done, and adopter will also need to continue with the process, as this will help this girl understand that she is loved, safe and wanted! Most of all, this is giving her confidence! UPDATE 12-16-20: Sweet Nellie J is beginning to come out of her shell. While this is a slow process for her, she has shown that she CAN and WILL be a great family member, given the time. She does love her crate--her safe place, and always has a clean, dry crate! She is working on her house manners. She will go out and do her business, but we are still working on doing both while outside consistently. She is a playful girl, but is scared very easily, which will we will work on. Learning to trust is a work in progress! Due to her being extremely scared, we are strongly suggesting this sweet girl have a FENCED IN YARD, if not, she can not be off leash at any time. After 3 weeks, she no longer tries to climb the fence, and we can let her go out with her foster gang with no worries that she will try to escape! 12-3-20: Nellie J is a beautiful, but very scared girl. Taken to Animal Control with 2 other dogs, unwanted, she found herself among dogs and strangers she didn't know. She APPEARS to be an Australian Kelpie/Terrier mix, around 2 years old, is 26 pounds, spayed, micro chipped and current on her vaccines, but sadly, like so many dogs in our area, Heartworm +. Nellie has begun her treatment. She does well with other dogs, but cats and children are unknown at this time. Since just getting to her foster home today, we have found that she is really scared and timid, and will try to jump a 4ft fence. She just couldn't get her body all the way over, which is a good thing, lol. She has short legs, but is extremely fast on those little legs! Hopefully, she will come out of her shell and not be so scared in the coming days. Due to her behavior at this time, we highly suggest a fenced yard, as if she gets away from you, you will not catch her. Once again, just a sweet, scared girl trying to figure out what is going on in her life. She will be a wonderful companion, given the chance! We will update once we learn more about her and her house/crate manners.
PLEASE, NO FIRST TIME DOG OWNERS OR RENTERS and MUST HAVE A VERIFIABLE, PAST 5 YEARS VET REFERENCE.

**GOOD VET REFERENCE IS REQUIRED**

animal.description:
Meet Wyatt, the stunning 2 year old, white, Harlequin Great Dane. This boy has clearly had a rough start with a lot of transitions and simply needs an experienced home who can help him navigate his special needs. You see, Wyatt is deaf and appears to have some vision issues as he is startled easily in low light/evenings. Wyatt was originally a part of a cruelty case which landed him in a different rescue group. Unfortunately, there were not any fosters experienced in handling his special needs, so BDHP stepped in to ensure this boy is fostered by someone who can manage him properly. Wyatt is house trained, crate trained, and leash trained though he requires a gentle leader due to pulling. He does not appear interested in toys, but with love and trust may open up a bit to new experiences. Wyatt is good with cats and kids, though we suggest older children only who can appreciate and respect his needs and a more quiet household. He is a bit insecure around other dogs and there has been an unprovoked aggressive incident in a prior home which BDHP will try to get to the bottom of while he is in foster care. Wyatt truly needs an adopter who can give him the time and space to decompress and settle into his forever home. With limited senses, this poor boy has to be so lost! He truly loves his humans and wants to be close to them at all times. He also loves the outdoors, so some adventures would certainly help build his confidence and bond! Do you feel you could be Wyatt's final destination?

Giant Breed Experienced Homes Only.

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

animal.description:
Dagny is an approximately 3 year-old female husky mix that was out of time at a local animal control over the holiday. She is such a SWEET girl once she gets comfortable with you. Dagny loves running and playing with the huskies. Dagny Is about 40 pounds. We are working on some basic commands. She would benefit from some rules, boundaries, structure and lots of love but what Puppy wouldn't?

Dagny is the most lovable hot mess ever!

She LOVES toys! Squeaky toys, chewy toys stuffed toys that need to have their squeakers removed. She loves them all.

She also loves other dogs! Unless they get near her toys, her food, her bed or her person.

She would love to have a sibling, but some boundaries will have to be established and feeding MUST be in her crate. She lacks impulse control but we are working on that.

She is also super loving and cuddly. She LOVES belly rubs and any other pets! She will sit for hours as long as she's being loved on. She also likes to sleep on the bed.

Dagny has anxiety when left in her crate. She hates being away from her human. This is a work in progress, and will take some time and patience. A lot of patience.

animal.description: Auggie loves having fun! This sweet 2-year-old boy looks to be a Boxer and Shepherd mix. He gets along great with other dogs and loves to play. He has been around young children and is very gentle. Auggie walks well on leash and enjoys going on adventures in the car. He does need to refine his manners, such as learning he doesn't need to jump up and give hugs to everyone, but he has mastered his housetraining! Auggie is very smart and knows his basic commands. He loves to play with his foster dog siblings and would be happiest with a dog sibling in his forever home that likes to play as much as he does; romping around outside with a furry friend sounds like the perfect life to Mr. Auggie! If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Auggie, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! If you are a previous Labs and More adopter or have already been approved and assigned an adoption coach, please reach out to your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: All Jimmy wants is to live a simple life. He's a simple guy who enjoys simple pleasures. Jimmy is a sweet soul who has been through a lot. He can be super shy at first but once he gets to know you he is a very active and playful pup. Jimmy is still learning exactly how to be a dog, and he is not too keen on pets and eye contact, but hey, who does like being touched or stared at by a stranger? Jimmy is looking for someone who is going to take the time to earn his trust, so he knows that they will be a worthwhile lifelong companion. But don't worry, Jimmy is not above being bribed with some yummy snacks. Throw some carrots his way and he just might crumble! Jimmy would love to have a nice safe place that is solely his space. When he is in one of his braver moods, he likes to come out to play and explore. However, he needs a safe zone where he can retreat to when he gets startled. He will soon 'recharge and emerge once again. As Jimmy starts to get more comfortable, he wants to spend more time with you, but he doesn't want you to know it. He'll follow you around the house, but he likes to play hide and seek - if you turn and look at him he'll duck behind the table or the kitchen island. He will also sniff your elbows and toes when you're sitting down but jump out of the way if you try to sneak in a pet. Jimmy is constantly discovering new things about this world and is becoming more confident every day. He is sure to make your heart melt as you watch him grow into the best version of himself. Come meet this precious boy!

animal.description:
UPDATE: JAN 24th.DUKE HAS AN ADOPTION PENDING. WE WILL KNOW MORE IN THE NEXT SEVERAL WEEKS IF HE IS ADOPTED. PLEASE CHECK BACK! 

PLEASE EMAIL US DIRECTLY AT CROSSOURPAWS@GMAIL.COM SO WE CAN RESPOND IN A TIMELY MANNER.

Duke is our special-needs, little-husky-boy who is loving and smart but comes with a few quirks . He is 11 months old,  weighs 45 lbs (may reach 60 lbs) and recently neutered.  Duke will need a dog-experienced, owner that can help improve his impulse control and anxieties. Duke is best in a home with kids over 12. He is well mannered with other dogs and is social with dog-friendly cats.

Duke’s new owner MUST employ only positive-training-methods and will need to be patient as he learns. He is best with a quiet but active family - homes with a safe, secure yard preferred.  We will insist Duke remain on his raw diet as he does not do well on highly processed foods such as kibble. Duke is house and crate-trained in his foster home, however may need reminders once moved.

To apply for Duke, visit our website at crossourpawsrescue.com and download our application. Once complete, email it back to crossourpaws@gmail.com. Include photos and video with your application. Local home (within GVRD) preferred. Detached homes must have a tall, secure fence as noted on our website.

PLEASE EMAIL US DIRECTLY AT CROSSOURPAWS@GMAIL.COM SO WE CAN RESPOND IN A TIMELY MANNER.

animal.description: Hi,  my name is Sylvia (HWTH#20234A).  I am a Shepherd mix, born 1/23/20 and I weigh 60 lbs.   My "sister" Perla (adopted) and  I were relinquished to Halfway to Home by my owners because they had too many dogs for which to care. I am still a puppy and I was overwhelmed by my new surroundings at first so I pretty much kept to myself.  With lots of TLC from the rescue folks I am now much more outgoing and I enjoy playing in my yard with my buddy Bruno (HWTH#20125).   I am ready to find a permanent place to call home where I can live inside and be part of a family.  I walk well on a leash, but would require a patient owner to house-train me because I have spent most of my life outside. An experienced handler and obedience training will help me understand what is expected of me. I get along great with other big dogs but I don’t know about smaller dogs or cats.  I would not do well in a household with children.  In order to ensure I get enough exercise, I need long walks and a big fenced yard for play.  I also enjoy other outdoor activities and going on car rides!  I do shed so I require regular brushing to keep my coat healthy.  Need to know anything else about me?  Would you like to make an appointment to meet me?  If so, please call Sandy at tele#661-824-4495 (this is a landline).  Thank you for checking in and I hope you will come see me soon.

BEAN IS AN ESCAPE ARTIST AND NEEDS AN EXPERIENCED, DILIGENT ADOPTER THAT LIVES IN AN APARTMENT OR HAS A DOUBLE GATED YARD. AS A YOUNG DOG THAT JUST CAME INTO OUR RESCUE HE IS NOT COMPLETELY HOUSEBROKEN AND IS STILL LEARNING TO WALK ON A LEASH. HE WOULD DO BEST IN A HOME WITHOUT CHILDREN AND THAT HAS AN EXISTING PLAYFUL DOG HIS SIZE (NO LARGE BREEDS).

My name is Bean and I'm an 11 month old Chihuahua/Dachshund mix. I'm currently being fostered with one of my littermates. We were owner surrenders but The Rescue Train has taken us aboard and is giving us a ride to our forever home!

I am sweet and snuggly, but being a young adult, I have an adventurous side too. I can be very curious, fearless, and have boundless energy! I need a savvy adopter that will provide plenty of structure and training to help me become a good canine citizen. 

---
If you are interested in adopting BEAN please fill out our adoption application on www.therescuetrain.org. Applications are required PRIOR to meeting one of our animals and are used to set up a safe and successful adoption. Please don't be shy and answer the questions thoroughly. To learn more about our entire process please visit www.therescuetrain.org and click on the "Adopt" page.

PLEASE NOTE: WE DO NOT OWN A FACILITY. Our animals are in private foster homes. If you are interested in adopting one of our animals please fill out our online application. Or check our mobile adoption schedule on our home page.

*APPLICANT MUST BE AT LEAST 21 YEARS OLD*
*APPLICANT MUST LIVE IN LOS ANGELES CITY*

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING?
PLEASE FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE: www.therescuetrain.org

animal.description:
My name is Mindy and I am the mommy of 11 beautiful babies that are finding their forever homes! I love to be with my foster family and get all the attention that I can get. However, there is one thing that I love more than snuggles and that is food! It is my most favorite thing ever and I cannot wait for the next meal. I could use some training to work on my basic commands and I hear that they give you treats so you know I am all for that!

I love being outside and my nose takes me on a lot of adventures. I would love to find an active family that would take me lots of places to explore new things. I enjoy playing with my foster siblings and my 11 beautiful puppies. My foster family also has cats and I love to chase them so I will do better in a home that does not have cats. I am a professional kisser and will give you kisses whenever you want. I enjoy being on the couch and snuggling with my foster family.

I have raised 11 puppies and I am exhausted! I can't wait to be settled in my forever home with you!


--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Dory is about 9 months and weighs around 40 pounds currently.  According to the person who surrendered her to animal control she is a lab/husky mix.  She is a little shy when she first meets you mainly because she is not sure what you want from her but she warms up quickly once she knows she can trust you.  She is a happy playful girl overall and loves other dogs.   Because she is nervous in new situations we would not recommend her with young active children.  She is not aggressive but their quick movements could scare her and make her run away.  She would do best in a home with another dog to follow and a fenced yard.  If you have room for two, she and Mimosa are buddies and would be great together.

All of our dogs are fostered in our homes so we know their temperaments.  They are spayed or neutered, up to date on shots, de-wormed, heartworm tested (and treated if necessary), and on flea and heartworm prevention. animal.description:
Annie is a 5-6 year old blood hound and she has a super duper sad story, she was used by a back yard breeder her entire life and when her body started failing her they dumped her at a rural shelter. Annie was 46 pounds- literally nothing but skin and bones, heart worm positive, and she wasn’t expected to live and so was put on the euthanasia list.  fortunately for her the shelter allowed us to tag her and save her life! It’s devastating to think of how her life was for so many years, but dogs are amazing and she still loves humans and does well with other large male dogs. We haven’t had many extremely reliable female dogs to test her with over the last year but the few that we did were really scared of her size- so I can’t say that she does well with females to be on the safe side.
Annie has been at our kennel facility for 14 months now and has had some interest throughout the year but people either have cats, smaller dogs, or female dogs which rules them out for adopting Annie. She is potty trained, fully vetted, and on her last round of heart worm treatment to be negative. She would do best in a home as an only pet or with another large friendly male dog, she also does well with children 2 years and over. 

ALL children should be at least AGE 5 to be approved for adoption!

Fill out an application at our website below to be considered for adoption.  This dog is available in the NJ Area.  We will contact you if we need further information.  We cannot directly reply to all applications.  

Please apply directly at WWW.BIGDOGRESCUEPROJECT.ORG/Adopt.

Our adoption fee of $425 includes  age appropriate vaccinations, microchipping and transport expenses. Spay/Neuter at 6 months of age is provided at select vets to NJ residents for $20. Details provided upon adoption. 

Application will be accepted and an adopter chosen based on the needs of the dog.  We will contact you if you are chosen to adopt.  

Applications can be made at bigdogrescueproject.org/adopt.  Please use the NJ Application. Thank you for considering Big Dog Rescue Project.

These donations help offset the cost of routine veterinary care, medical expenses, and other necessities while the rescue animal is in our care. animal.description:
Kiki came to PAWS after being overlooked in a large city shelter for almost a year. 
She is beautiful, large, very strong (she doesn't know her own strength) and always happy. Kiki is learning to walk on leash - she is a puller, ever exuberant to just keep moving forward. She does seem to have a prey drive, so we don't suggest a home with small animals. She enjoys walking with calm dogs, and she is not reactive to the dogs in the kennel where she is currently staying. She is very food motivated, and we are working on her manners when it comes to taking treats, so we would say no small children -- she hasn't shown guarding, but she gets very excited by high value treats... Kiki is about 6 years old and has obviously had puppies in her past. She will be spayed soon and would LOVE to find a calm, loving home with large dog experience where she can decompress and live a great life. She will make a wonderful and loving companion.

animal.description:
This 9 year old cockapoo was surrendered when his owner was moving out of state... he’s a nervous guy but bonds quickly and very sweet with his people once he feels safe.  Wink’s routine vet exam and bloodwork that all our seniors get on arrival revealed that he has kidney disease, high blood pressure, dry eye, and an ear infection and he’s on a special diet to help slow down progression of his kidney disease and medication for the other conditions.  We intercepted him before he was going to be surrendered to a local county shelter where with his medical issues and fearful personality he would have had a tough time.  
Wink is in foster care and doing well, and looking for a forever home where he will continue to get proper medical care and grooming for life.  He gets along with other dogs and is looking for a calmer low-traffic adult home without a lot of people coming and going and someone who will give him time to settle in.  Email njwoof@cs.com for an appointment to meet him.

animal.description:
Meet Mia!

Interested in meeting Mia? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Diego! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:
-Personality: Active, food motivated and playful 
-Can Live with Kids: Yes, 16 and older. 
-Can Live with Cats: No - likely high prey drive and has never lived with cats. 
-Can Live with Dogs: Yes, with another respectful and tolerant dog - introduction will be done here at WHS.
-Can do Apartment Living: No thank you, I am too high energy and need more space! 
-Potty Trained: Yes 
-Bite History: None 
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes, one private lesson 
-Leash Trained: Still working on not pulling on the leash. 
-Energy Level: High! 
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: Yes, a neuter 
-Additional Information: Despite Diego being an older dog, he is very active and playful! Diego spent most of his life outside and for this reason would not be a match for an apartment and would benefit from a large, fenced in yard. Diego still need to learn to take treats and toys gently making a home with older children or only adults the most appropriate match. Diego is strong and can be reactive towards other dogs through a fence or on a leash, attending a positive reward based training session would help him work on this and will help him bond to his new owner.

animal.description: If you're looking for a big, sweet, and loving boy, than Rocko is the dog for you! Whether it's lounging on the couch or splashing around in the kiddie pool, his favorite activity, Rocko loves spending quality time with his people and any dogs he gets to call brother or sister. His favorite toys are tennis balls and plushes, but he knows how valuable they are to you and him so he does a great job of keeping them in one piece. Treats are really the way to his heart, though, and he'll do anything to earn a tasty snack. No one's ever called Rocko a shy boy, and his friendly personality is immediately open to anyone who meets him. Also, Rocko is both house and crate trained so there's no need to worry about any accidental messes in the house. All Rocko needs is a place to settle in, be himself, and for someone to return all the love he has to give, and he'll be the best companion you've ever seen! To learn more about adopting Rocko from foster care, email asoanimaladoption@austintexas.gov! I weigh approximately 72 lbs. Click here to view my paperwork.

animal.description:
Please read our adoption requirements at http://gsrne.org/requirements-for-adopting-from-gsrne before contacting us about this dog.
Koda is an active boy with lots of energy. He loves to go on any adventure, be it a walk, car ride or just playing in the fenced yard.  He absolutely LOVES playing fetch and being chased by the female German Shepherd in his foster home.
Because Koda missed out on being socialized when he was a puppy, he needs a gradual introduction to new people and does best with people who know how to give him time to get comfortable. Koda has become a real cuddler, loves to be petted, and his tail starts to wag any time his foster Mom or Dad walk by him.
Koda came into GSRNE because his lack of exposure to new situations had led to his being nervous and dog-reactive.  In his original home, he had run through the electric fence in his yard, grabbed a small dog being walked past the property, and his owners were told they needed to rehome him.  He had lived with another dog though, so we decided to give him a chance to get comfortable with the GSD in his foster home.  By taking the introduction gradually and walking the dogs together, it worked out nicely. He can still be reactive when he sees another dog while he’s out for a walk, but he’s learning to look to his person for direction.  He will need continued training, patience, and lots of new experiences, to continue helping him to learn to be comfortable in most situations.
During the first weeks in his foster home, Koda would submissively urinate when he felt uncomfortable or pressured in many situations; as when attaching a leash, removing or putting on his collar, or being examined. Creating positive association, and teaching him new behaviors have helped him gain confidence and learn to trust the people in his foster home. He is learning that these things that previously made him nervous, can be positive rewarding experiences.
The ideal home for Koda will be with people who have experience with the breed, have the time, knowledge, and patience to continue working with him in the ways we’ve found to be successful.  Koda would also enjoy the company of a friendly, playful female dog to play the chase games he really enjoys in the yard, and help burn off some of his energy.  
More photos: https://gsrne.org/gsrne-live/our-available-dogs/

animal.description:
Don't be shocked when your history book mentions me; I am Hamilton, 60 lbs of awesome Aussie.  I am 3 years old and may not be able to write my own papers, but I'm happy to lay under your desk while you work.  I like a quiet life of snuggling, chewing my toys, and playing games with my people. I love learning, and I already know the basics like sit, down, "hup" to jump on something, and "off" to hop off of something.  I am working on my leash skills, and they are pretty good, but sometimes I get distracted by things around me. I know where my kennel is, how to go in, and I can hang out in it if you need me to. I can be a little nervous about new places, things, and sometimes people so I will need someone that understands and is willing to learn how to help me through that. I have epilepsy and am currently on medication, but I love snacks, so I have no problem taking my meds. I am a private fellow so would like a privacy fenced yard and a home without other pets or kids. I love the weather and such here so please local applications only! I can't wait to tell the story about how you walked in and my heart went 'BOOM!'


My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

Please contact Debbie (Deb@AmericanbulldogRescue.org) for more information about this pet.

Dog: JaxAge: about 6-7 years oldWeight: 65 lbsLocation: Langhorne, PANicknames: JackGood with other dogs?: Yes and No, he's had some hiccups meeting certain dogs recently. His history is that he's done well with other dogs. A confident female seems to be the best match for him to live with or be the only dog.Good with cats? NoGood with children? NoActivity Preference: Go with the flow, professional napper, likes a walkIQ: Pretty smartJax's favorite things: Lots of belly rubs and his humansJax is good at: meeting people, staying in a crate, riding in a carIdeal home: a fenced yard, no children or cats
MEET JAX
Jax is a very sweet, sensitive boy who enjoys low-key, together time with is favorite human. He seems much younger than his estimated age of 6-7 years. He's a really good boy totally house trained, crate trained, good on a leash, and well-behaved. He's a mostly quiet boy, he will occasionally bark to 'scare away' people walking by or coming to the door. But we think he's all talk (don't tell him that though) we let him think he's super scary! LOL. He's just adorable with those pouty lips and soul-searching eyes. He will melt your heart! Jax is very friendly and does well meeting company. He loves spending his days with his foster family either working from home, going for a walk, or just relaxing. Jax is the perfect best friend for a lucky adopter out there.

PLEASE READ: Adopters will not be considered without completing an application. Please visit www.AmericanBulldogRescue.org to apply! Remember - Adoption is always the best option! If you can't help by adopting a homeless pet, please consider making a tax-deductible donation to American Bulldog Rescue, 4 Terry Drive, Suite 1D Newtown, PA 18940 or paypal AmericanBulldogRescue@verizon.net. We cannot place dogs in homes with children under 10 unless that dog has lived with kids or is in a foster home with kids. Thank you.To be considered for adoption, you must apply using our free, online application. Our dogs are fostered in our volunteers' homes, not in a central shelter/location. Only approved applicants are put into contact with the foster family to setup a meeting with the foster dog. Visit our Adoption Policies web page for more information and a link to our application: http://americanbulldogrescue.org/adoption-policies/.

animal.description:
MEET PRIME!

My name is Optimus Prime but everyone calls me Prime. I'm a medium to tall lanky fella. They say I'm a lab mix, but nobody knows for sure. I'm 50 lbs and 5 1/2 years old so I'm well past the puppy stage but I still love to play tug of war and fetch. Foster Mom says I'm part reindeer because of the way I like to jump and prance.I am very good with other dogs. If they don't want to talk to me, I just go on about my business. Their loss! Haven't met any cats but don't care about squirrels and deer so I reckon cats won't bother me either.

I know basic obedience but will pull on a leash to get to all the yummy smells! I am house broken and crate trained.

Sudden noises startle me a little and I need people to give me a moment to warm up to them, but then it's all good and I'm jumping all over the place.I sure would love a home with another dog to keep me company and build my self confidence. And I would love to go on long walks with you. I think it's best if your kids are a little older as I'm spooked a little easily. Although I'm getting more confident and comfortable as I spend time with my foster family.So if you're looking for a nice handsome fella who is quietly playful, come meet me.

Optimus Prime is up-to-date, microchipped, and his adoption fee is $350.

animal.description:
In Foster/Available To Adopt 

***Only accepting applications with other dogs***

Dona is about 6 years old and from the Dog Meat Trade (Yulin Dog Meat Festival) in China. 

Notes from her foster:

"She loves my boyfriend. She idolizes him, and is more apt to approach men over women. She did have a bit of separation anxiety when he left the room in the beginning.

She lets me pet her and feed her kibble out of my hand but she’s definitely more hesitant of me. I think she’s more partial towards men and she’ll do best with one in the equation over a single female adopter.

She’s not a fan of sleeping in a crate, but loves sleeping on blankets in the living room with her. 

She loves walks! She’s the most outgoing and energetic when she’s on them. When you pick up her leash she goes crazy! It’s very cute to see.

She loves bunched up blankets and fluffy beds! She snuggles right into them and it’s the most relaxed I see her. 

Sudden movements and noises scare her so a house without children is probably best. She likes our 5-year-old dog more so than our puppy but she’s content with both and seems to fit right into the pact. I think a home with other dogs would be good for her, but she would do well with a perfect home without dogs as well. 

Overall she is the sweetest, timid little thing, and she’ll need a home that has a lot of patience. She’s just had such a tough hand over the years, but despite all of it she wants to love and trust. We can tell it’s just gonna take some time!


Apply to foster at: 
https://www.animalhopeandwellness.org/fosterprocessandapplication

Apply to adopt at: 
https://www.animalhopeandwellness.org/adoptionprocessandapplication

We are by appointment only. You must submit and have an approved application before meeting AHWF animals.

For General Adopt/Foster Inquiries: adopt@animalhopeandwellness.org
